{"title_page": "Mary Wiseman (actress)", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Infobox person\t\n| name         = Mary Wiseman\t\n| image        = Mary Wiseman SDCC 2017.jpg\n| caption      = Wiseman at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]\t\t\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1985|07|30}}\n| birth_place  = \n| education    = [[Boston University]] ([[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]])<br />[[Juilliard School]] {{small|([[Graduate diploma|GrDip]])}}\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 2012\u2013present\t\n| spouse       =  {{marriage|Noah Averbach-Katz|2019}}\n| children     = \n}}\n\n'''Mary Wiseman''' (born July 30, 1985) is an American actress who is known for playing Ensign Sylvia Tilly in ''[[Star Trek: Discovery]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/STAR-TREK-DISCOVERY-Beams-Up-Two-New-Starfleet-Crew-Members-20170307|title=STAR TREK: DISCOVERY Beams Up Two New Starfleet Crew Members|first=TV News|last=Desk|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWiseman is the youngest daughter of Dorothy and Kevin Wiseman and has three older brothers. She grew up in [[Milford, Pennsylvania]] and [[Gaithersburg, Maryland]], attended the DC Shakespeare Theatre\u2019s high school outreach program, earned her BFA in Theatre Arts at Boston University,<ref name=\"archive.org\">{{cite web|url=http://18actors.com/whos-who/|title=Who\u2019s Who - 18 Actors|date=10 January 2016|url-status=bot: unknown|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110215424/http://18actors.com/whos-who/|archive-date=10 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"marymarry\">{{cite news |last1=La Gorce |first1=Tammy |title=A Life Frequently Apart, but an Enterprise They\u2019ll Boldly Take On |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/08/fashion/weddings/a-life-frequently-apart-but-an-enterprise-theyll-boldly-take-on.html |accessdate=14 March 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=8 March 2019}}</ref> and studied between 2011 and 2015 at [[Juilliard School]]'s Drama Division where one of her classmates was future ''Star Trek: Discovery'' collaborator [[Mary Chieffo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Juilliard Drama Sets 2014-15 Season: 'VERA STARK,' RABBIT HOLE, ANGELS IN AMERICA & More|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Juilliard-Drama-Sets-2014-15-Season-VERA-STARK-RABBIT-HOLE-ANGELS-IN-AMERICA-More-20140624|work=Broadway World|date=24 June 2014|location=New York City}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Juilliard Students Form G44 Productions, Release First Short Film|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Juilliard-Students-Form-G44-Productions-Release-First-Short-Film-20130705|work=Broadway World|date=5 June 2013|location=New York City}}</ref><ref name=\"archive.org\"/> Another classmate is actor [[Noah Averbach-Katz]], whom she started dating in 2013. The couple got married on February 16, 2019.<ref name=\"marymarry\" />\n\n==Career==\nWiseman's stage roles have included Nitzan Halperin's ''Sow and Weep'' (2008, Boston University College of Fine Arts in New York),<ref>{{cite news|title=Photo Flash: Boston University's InCite Festival in NYC|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Photo-Flash-Boston-Universitys-InCite-Festival-in-NYC-20080221|work=Broadway World|date=21 February 2008|location=New York City}}</ref> Ariel Carson's ''I Wanted it to Have a How & I Wanted it to Have a Verb'' (2011, [[Dixon Place]])<ref>{{cite news|title=Dixon Place Releases Upcoming Spring Performance Calendar|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Dixon-Place-Releases-Upcoming-Spring-Performance-Calendar-20110111|work=Broadway World|date=11 January 2011|location=New York City}}</ref> and Betsy/Lindsay in ''[[Clybourne Park]]'' (2013, Chautauqua Theater Company).<ref>\n* {{cite news|title=Harris Yulin, Candy Buckley & More Set for Chautauqua Theater Company's 30th Anniversary Season|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/buffalo/article/Harris-Yulin-Candy-Buckley-More-Set-for-Chautauqua-Theater-Companys-30th-Anniversary-Season-20130617|work=Broadway World|date=17 June 2013|location=New York City}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.berkshireeagle.com/stories/rewriting-the-happy-ending-world-premiere-of-romance-novels-for-dummies,201232|title=Rewriting the happy ending: World premiere of 'Romance Novels for Dummies'|publisher=}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.berkshirefinearts.com/07-24-2016_romance-novels-for-dummies-at-wtf.htm|title=Romance Novels for Dummies at WTF - Berkshire Fine Arts|first=Charles|last=Giuliano|website=www.berkshirefinearts.com}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.tfana.org/about/production-history/octoroon/creative-team-cast|title=Creative Team & Cast|date=6 February 2015|publisher=}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/theater-dance/2016/07/14/rebel-and-her-romance-novels/s1PZrdrmeOW3gyHtP9c5oL/story.html|title=A rebel and her \u2018Romance Novels\u2019 - The Boston Globe|publisher=}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://wtfestival.org/main-events/wtf-happened-in-2016/|title=WTF HAPPENED IN 2016 - Williamstown Theatre Festival|website=wtfestival.org}}\n* [http://berkshirereview.net/sex-love-and-marriage-come-to-williamstown-legacy-off-the-main-road-and-kinship-at-the-williamstown-theatre-festival/ Michael Miller - Sex, Love, and Marriage come to Williamstown: Legacy, Off the Main Road, and Kinship at the Williamstown Theatre Festival - July 28, 2015 - August 11, 2015 - The Berkshire Review for the Arts]\n* {{cite web|url=https://hollyderr.com/2015/10/07/branden-jacobs-jenkins-an-octoroon/|title=Branden Jacobs-Jenkins\u2019 An Octoroon|date=7 October 2015|publisher=}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://cnycafemomus.com/2015/07/july-18-wtfestival-off-the-main-road/|title=July 18 WTFestival: Off the Main Road - CNY Caf\u00e9 Momus|date=27 July 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nWiseman has performed in productions and workshops of new plays in Playwrights\u2019 theatres like PS 122, The Public, Soho Rep, and New York Theatre Workshop.<ref name=\"archive.org\"/>\n\nWiseman appeared in the TV series ''[[Longmire (TV series)|Longmire]]'' as Meg Joyce, a nurse and love interest for the character Archie \"The Ferg\" Ferguson.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thisisinsider.com/star-trek-discovery-cast-real-life-2017-9|title=Here's what the cast of 'Star Trek: Discovery' looks like in real life|work=INSIDER|access-date=2018-02-20}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Film, television and video games \n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2012\n|''Craft & Burn''\n|Senior Server\n|\"Part IV\", \"Part IX\"\n|-\n|2014\n|''Three Dates''\n|Stacey\n|Short\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Netflix Presents: The Characters]]''\n|Shannon\n|\"[[John Early (comedian)|John Early]]\"\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Difficult People]]''\n|\n|\"High Alert\"\n|-\n|2016\u201317\n|''[[Longmire (TV series)|Longmire]]''\n|Meg Joyce\n|Recurring role (seasons 5\u20136)\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|''[[Baskets (TV series)|Baskets]]''\n|Trinity\n|\"Freaks\", \"Yard Sale\", \"Crash\"\n|-\n|2017\u2013present\n|''[[Star Trek: Discovery]]''\n|[[List of Star Trek: Discovery characters#Sylvia Tilly|Sylvia Tilly]]\n|Main role\n|-\n|2018\n|''Health to the King''\n|Nurse\n|Short, filming\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Star Trek: Short Treks]]''\n| Sylvia Tilly\n| Episode: \"Runaway\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Room 104]]''\n| Josie\n| Episode: \"Josie & Me\"\n|-\n| 2018\u20132019\n| ''[[Star Trek: Online]]''\n| Sylvia Tilly/Sylvia Tilly (mirror)\n| Voice<ref name=\"Discovery Culber\">{{cite web |url=https://trekmovie.com/2018/07/26/star-trek-online-launching-age-of-discovery-tie-in-to-star-trek-discovery-this-fall/|title=Star Trek Online Launching \u2018Age Of Discovery\u2019 Tie-in To \u2018Star Trek: Discovery\u2019 This Fall|date=July 26, 2018|website=TrekMovie.com|accessdate=July 26, 2018|first=TrekMovie.com|last=Staff}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mary Wiseman}}\n* {{IMDB name|nm6384402}}\n* {{IBDB name|502365}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wiseman, Mary}}\n[[Category:Actresses from Maryland]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Boston University College of Fine Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Juilliard School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gaithersburg, Maryland]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:People from Milford, Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Infobox person\t\n| name         = Mary Wiseman\t\n| image        = Mary Wiseman SDCC 2017.jpg\n| caption      = Wiseman at the 2017 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]\t\t\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1985|07|30}}\n| birth_place  = \n| education    = [[Boston University]] ([[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]])<br />[[Juilliard School]] {{small|([[Graduate diploma|GrDip]])}}\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 2012\u2013present\t\n| spouse       =  {{marriage|Noah Averbach-Katz|2019}}\n| children     = \n}}\n\n'''Mary Wiseman''' (born July 30, 1985) is an American actress who is known for playing Ensign Sylvia Tilly in ''[[Star Trek: Discovery]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/STAR-TREK-DISCOVERY-Beams-Up-Two-New-Starfleet-Crew-Members-20170307|title=STAR TREK: DISCOVERY Beams Up Two New Starfleet Crew Members|first=TV News|last=Desk|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWiseman is the youngest daughter of Dorothy and Kevin Wiseman and has three older brothers. She grew up in [[Milford, Pennsylvania]] and [[Gaithersburg, Maryland]], attended the DC Shakespeare Theatre\u2019s high school outreach program, earned her BFA in Theatre Arts at Boston University,<ref name=\"archive.org\">{{cite web|url=http://18actors.com/whos-who/|title=Who\u2019s Who - 18 Actors|date=10 January 2016|url-status=bot: unknown|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110215424/http://18actors.com/whos-who/|archive-date=10 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"marymarry\">{{cite news |last1=La Gorce |first1=Tammy |title=A Life Frequently Apart, but an Enterprise They\u2019ll Boldly Take On |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/08/fashion/weddings/a-life-frequently-apart-but-an-enterprise-theyll-boldly-take-on.html |accessdate=14 March 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=8 March 2019}}</ref> and studied between 2011 and 2015 at [[Juilliard School]]'s Drama Division where one of her classmates was future ''Star Trek: Discovery'' collaborator [[Mary Chieffo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Juilliard Drama Sets 2014-15 Season: 'VERA STARK,' RABBIT HOLE, ANGELS IN AMERICA & More|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Juilliard-Drama-Sets-2014-15-Season-VERA-STARK-RABBIT-HOLE-ANGELS-IN-AMERICA-More-20140624|work=Broadway World|date=24 June 2014|location=New York City}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Juilliard Students Form G44 Productions, Release First Short Film|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Juilliard-Students-Form-G44-Productions-Release-First-Short-Film-20130705|work=Broadway World|date=5 June 2013|location=New York City}}</ref><ref name=\"archive.org\"/> Another classmate is actor [[Noah Averbach-Katz]], whom she started dating in 2013. The couple got married on February 16, 2019, at the Full Moon Resort in [[Big Indian, New York]].<ref name=\"marymarry\" />\n\n==Career==\nWiseman's stage roles have included Nitzan Halperin's ''Sow and Weep'' (2008, Boston University College of Fine Arts in New York),<ref>{{cite news|title=Photo Flash: Boston University's InCite Festival in NYC|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Photo-Flash-Boston-Universitys-InCite-Festival-in-NYC-20080221|work=Broadway World|date=21 February 2008|location=New York City}}</ref> Ariel Carson's ''I Wanted it to Have a How & I Wanted it to Have a Verb'' (2011, [[Dixon Place]])<ref>{{cite news|title=Dixon Place Releases Upcoming Spring Performance Calendar|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Dixon-Place-Releases-Upcoming-Spring-Performance-Calendar-20110111|work=Broadway World|date=11 January 2011|location=New York City}}</ref> and Betsy/Lindsay in ''[[Clybourne Park]]'' (2013, Chautauqua Theater Company).<ref>\n* {{cite news|title=Harris Yulin, Candy Buckley & More Set for Chautauqua Theater Company's 30th Anniversary Season|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/buffalo/article/Harris-Yulin-Candy-Buckley-More-Set-for-Chautauqua-Theater-Companys-30th-Anniversary-Season-20130617|work=Broadway World|date=17 June 2013|location=New York City}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.berkshireeagle.com/stories/rewriting-the-happy-ending-world-premiere-of-romance-novels-for-dummies,201232|title=Rewriting the happy ending: World premiere of 'Romance Novels for Dummies'|publisher=}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.berkshirefinearts.com/07-24-2016_romance-novels-for-dummies-at-wtf.htm|title=Romance Novels for Dummies at WTF - Berkshire Fine Arts|first=Charles|last=Giuliano|website=www.berkshirefinearts.com}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.tfana.org/about/production-history/octoroon/creative-team-cast|title=Creative Team & Cast|date=6 February 2015|publisher=}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/theater-dance/2016/07/14/rebel-and-her-romance-novels/s1PZrdrmeOW3gyHtP9c5oL/story.html|title=A rebel and her \u2018Romance Novels\u2019 - The Boston Globe|publisher=}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://wtfestival.org/main-events/wtf-happened-in-2016/|title=WTF HAPPENED IN 2016 - Williamstown Theatre Festival|website=wtfestival.org}}\n* [http://berkshirereview.net/sex-love-and-marriage-come-to-williamstown-legacy-off-the-main-road-and-kinship-at-the-williamstown-theatre-festival/ Michael Miller - Sex, Love, and Marriage come to Williamstown: Legacy, Off the Main Road, and Kinship at the Williamstown Theatre Festival - July 28, 2015 - August 11, 2015 - The Berkshire Review for the Arts]\n* {{cite web|url=https://hollyderr.com/2015/10/07/branden-jacobs-jenkins-an-octoroon/|title=Branden Jacobs-Jenkins\u2019 An Octoroon|date=7 October 2015|publisher=}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://cnycafemomus.com/2015/07/july-18-wtfestival-off-the-main-road/|title=July 18 WTFestival: Off the Main Road - CNY Caf\u00e9 Momus|date=27 July 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nWiseman has performed in productions and workshops of new plays in Playwrights\u2019 theatres like PS 122, The Public, Soho Rep, and New York Theatre Workshop.<ref name=\"archive.org\"/>\n\nWiseman appeared in the TV series ''[[Longmire (TV series)|Longmire]]'' as Meg Joyce, a nurse and love interest for the character Archie \"The Ferg\" Ferguson.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thisisinsider.com/star-trek-discovery-cast-real-life-2017-9|title=Here's what the cast of 'Star Trek: Discovery' looks like in real life|work=INSIDER|access-date=2018-02-20}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Film, television and video games \n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|2012\n|''Craft & Burn''\n|Senior Server\n|\"Part IV\", \"Part IX\"\n|-\n|2014\n|''Three Dates''\n|Stacey\n|Short\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Netflix Presents: The Characters]]''\n|Shannon\n|\"[[John Early (comedian)|John Early]]\"\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Difficult People]]''\n|\n|\"High Alert\"\n|-\n|2016\u201317\n|''[[Longmire (TV series)|Longmire]]''\n|Meg Joyce\n|Recurring role (seasons 5\u20136)\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|''[[Baskets (TV series)|Baskets]]''\n|Trinity\n|\"Freaks\", \"Yard Sale\", \"Crash\"\n|-\n|2017\u2013present\n|''[[Star Trek: Discovery]]''\n|[[List of Star Trek: Discovery characters#Sylvia Tilly|Sylvia Tilly]]\n|Main role\n|-\n|2018\n|''Health to the King''\n|Nurse\n|Short, filming\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Star Trek: Short Treks]]''\n| Sylvia Tilly\n| Episode: \"Runaway\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Room 104]]''\n| Josie\n| Episode: \"Josie & Me\"\n|-\n| 2018\u20132019\n| ''[[Star Trek: Online]]''\n| Sylvia Tilly/Sylvia Tilly (mirror)\n| Voice<ref name=\"Discovery Culber\">{{cite web |url=https://trekmovie.com/2018/07/26/star-trek-online-launching-age-of-discovery-tie-in-to-star-trek-discovery-this-fall/|title=Star Trek Online Launching \u2018Age Of Discovery\u2019 Tie-in To \u2018Star Trek: Discovery\u2019 This Fall|date=July 26, 2018|website=TrekMovie.com|accessdate=July 26, 2018|first=TrekMovie.com|last=Staff}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mary Wiseman}}\n* {{IMDB name|nm6384402}}\n* {{IBDB name|502365}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wiseman, Mary}}\n[[Category:Actresses from Maryland]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Boston University College of Fine Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Juilliard School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gaithersburg, Maryland]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:People from Milford, Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Lovemankind83", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Wiseman_(actress)"}
{"title_page": "Baz Luhrmann", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian director, writer, and producer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Baz Luhrmann\n| image              = Baz Luhrmann.jpg\n| caption            = Luhrmann in 2013\n| birth_name         = Mark Anthony Luhrmann\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1962|9|17}}\n| birth_place        = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia<ref>{{cite web |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800026871/bio|title=Baz Luhrmann biodata|work=Yahoo! Movies|accessdate=14 November 2009}}</ref>\n| alma_mater         = [[Narrabeen Sports High School]]\n| occupation         = Film director, screenwriter, producer, actor\n| years_active       = 1982\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Catherine Martin (designer)|Catherine Martin]]|1997}}\n| children           = 2\n}}\n\n'''Baz Luhrmann''' (born '''Mark Anthony Luhrmann''', 17 September 1962) is an Australian director, writer, and producer with projects spanning film, television, opera, theatre, music, and recording industries. He is regarded by many as a contemporary example of an [[auteur]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/09/magazine/deep-inside-baz-luhrmanns-creative-chaos.html|title=Deep Inside Baz Luhrmann's Creative Chaos|last=Wallace|first=Amy|date=2014-02-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-25|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> for his style and deep involvement in the writing, directing, design, and musical components of all his work. He is the most commercially successful Australian director, with four of his films in the top ten highest worldwide grossing [[Australian films]] of all time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-08-01/top-10-australian-films-at-australian-box-office/6655808|title=Top 10 grossing Australian films of all time|date=2015-08-01|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/entertainment/movies/2016/12/30/best-australian-movies/|title=Australia's top 10 highest grossing films of all time|date=2016-12-30|work=The New Daily|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn the screen he is best known for his \"Red Curtain Trilogy,\" comprising his romantic comedy film ''[[Strictly Ballroom]]'' (1992), the romantic tragedy ''[[Romeo + Juliet|William Shakespeare's Romeo + Juliet]]'' (1996), and ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'' (2001). Following the trilogy, projects included ''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]'' (2008), ''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]'' (2013), and his television period drama ''[[The Get Down]]'' for [[Netflix]]. Additional projects include stage productions of [[Giacomo Puccini]]'s ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' for both the [[Australian Opera]] and [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] and ''[[Strictly Ballroom (musical)|Strictly Ballroom the Musical]]''.\n\nLuhrmann is equally known for his [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-nominated soundtracks for ''[[Moulin Rouge! Music from Baz Luhrmann's Film|Moulin Rouge!]]'' and [[The Great Gatsby: Music from Baz Luhrmann's Film|''The Great Gatsby'']], as well as his record label House of Iona, a co-venture with [[RCA Records]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6473231/baz-luhrmann-rca-to-launch-bazmark-label|title=Baz Luhrmann, RCA To Launch Bazmark Label|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-07-05}}</ref> Serving as producer on all of his musical soundtracks, he also holds writing credits on many of the individual tracks. His album ''[[Something for Everybody (Baz Luhrmann album)|Something For Everybody]]'' features music from many of his films and also includes his hit \"[[Everybody's Free (To Wear Sunscreen)]]\".\n\nLuhrmann's influence has extended outside the traditional realm of media and entertainment. Deeply involved in the fashion and art worlds, Luhrmann's ''[[No. 5 the Film]]'' for [[Chanel]] not only holds a [[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Record]] for the highest budget for an advertising commercial ever produced,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-expensive-advertisement-(commercial)-on-television/|title=Most expensive advertisement (commercial) on television|work=Guinness World Records|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> but pioneered the now commonplace genre of fashion film and [[branded content]]. Luhrmann works closely with the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]'s [[Anna Wintour Costume Center]], having chaired the annual [[Met Gala]] as well as producing a short film for the museum, celebrating [[Miuccia Prada]] and [[Elsa Schiaparelli]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/exhibitions/listings/2012/impossible-conversations/audio-and-video|title=Audio and Video {{!}} The Metropolitan Museum of Art|website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2018-01-25}}</ref> More recently he and his wife [[Catherine Martin (designer)|Catherine Martin]] have adapted their style for projects in events, retail, architecture and design with [[Barneys New York]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/baz-dazzled-barneys-new-york-holiday-windows-unveiling|title=Baz Dazzled: The Barneys New York Holiday Window Unveiling with Baz Luhrmann and Catherine Martin|work=Vogue|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en}}</ref> and developer and hotelier [[Alan Faena]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/what-looks-like-baz-luhrmann-838537|title=What It Looks Like When Baz Luhrmann Helps Design a Miami Hotel|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/annabel/2016/05/11/the-maestro-of-miami-beach-alan-faena-and-his-new-faena-hotel/|title=The Maestro of Miami Beach: Alan Faena and His New Faena Hotel|last=Abel|first=Ann|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLuhrmann was born in Sydney. His mother, Barbara Carmel (n\u00e9e Brennan), was a ballroom dance teacher and dress shop owner, and his father, Leonard Luhrmann, ran a petrol station and a movie theatre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/28/Baz-Luhrmann.html|title=Baz Luhrmann profile at|work=FilmReference.com}}</ref><ref>[http://www.couriermail.com.au/entertainment/movies/man-of-many-talents/story-e6freqex-1111118148222 \"Baz Luhrmann a man of many talents\"], ''[[The Courier-Mail]]'', 26 November 2008</ref><ref>[http://familytreemaker.genealogy.com/users/h/a/r/Jennifer-Harrison-Chisholm/WEBSITE-0001/UHP-0318.html Luhrmann-related genealogy site]</ref> He was raised in [[Herons Creek, New South Wales|Herons Creek]], a tiny rural settlement in northern [[New South Wales]]. He attended St&nbsp;Joseph's Hastings Regional School, [[Port Macquarie]] (1975\u20131978); [[St Paul's College, Manly|St Paul's Catholic College]], performing in the school's version of Shakespeare's ''[[Henry IV, Part 1]]'', and [[Narrabeen Sports High School]], where he met future collaborator [[Craig Pearce]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8P8aBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT14&q=Craig%20Pearce%20narrabeen%20sports%20high%20school|title=Baz Luhrmann: Interviews|last=Ryan|first=Tom|date=2014-11-05|publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi|isbn=9781626743007|language=en}}</ref>\n\nLuhrmann received the nickname \"Baz\" from his father, given to him because of his afro hair style, the name coming from the English [[Basil Brush]]. While still in high school, Luhrmann changed his name by deed poll to Bazmark, joining his nickname and birth name together.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/apr/23/baz-luhrmann-strictly-ballroom-the-musical-interview \"Baz Luhrmann: 'I've never waited for permission to do anything'&thinsp;\"] by Ryan Gilbey, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 24 April 2018</ref> In 1980 Luhrmann graduated high school and in the same year was cast opposite [[Judy Davis]] in the Australian film ''[[Winter of Our Dreams]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baz Luhrmann i(10 works by) (birth name: Mark Anthony Luhrmann) (a.k.a. Bazmark Anthony Luhrmann)|url=http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/OLD?id=A3x&idtype=oldid|work=AustLit|publisher=AustLit|accessdate=6 February 2014|year=2014}}</ref> In 1982 using the money he had earned from film and television experience he funded his own theatre company, The Bond Theatre Company, with future friends and collaborators Nelly Hooper and Gabrielle Mason. The company performed at [[Bondi Pavilion|the Pavilion at Sydney's Bondi Beach]]. At the same time he conceived and appeared in a controversial television documentary, ''Kids of the [[Kings Cross, New South Wales|Cross]]'', where Luhrmann, embedded as a character, lived with a group of street kids.<ref>{{IMDb title|id=2201089|title=Kids of the Cross}}</ref> In 1983, he began an acting course at the [[National Institute of Dramatic Art]]. He graduated in 1985 alongside [[Sonia Todd]], [[Catherine McClements]] and [[Justin Monjo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nida.edu.au/ALUMNI/default.aspx |title=NIDA Alumni |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014011919/http://www.nida.edu.au/ALUMNI/default.aspx |archivedate=14 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On [[Australia Day|26 January]] 1997, he married [[Catherine Martin (designer)|Catherine Martin]], a [[production designer]]; the couple have two children.\n\nLuhrmann supports the [[Melbourne Football Club|Melbourne Demons]] in the [[Australian Football League]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Beveridge|first1=Riley|title=Your AFL club's most famous supporters, from Barack Obama to Cam Newton|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/your-afl-clubs-most-famous-supporters-from-barack-obama-to-cam-newton/news-story/03eb54659866d587cf9c2cc4b9f3d8c5|website=Fox Sports|accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Films==\n[[File:BazLuhrmann2.png|thumb|Luhrmann in 2018]]\nAfter theatrical successes, including the original stage version of ''Strictly Ballroom'', Luhrmann moved into film and has directed five so far:\n*''[[Strictly Ballroom]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Romeo + Juliet]]'' (1996)\n*''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]'' (2008)\n*''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]'' (2013)\n\nThe modern film interpretation ''[[Romeo + Juliet]]'', starring [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] and [[Claire Danes]], defeated ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'' at the BAFTAs for best direction, music and screenplay. The film was celebrated at the Berlin Film Festival, where it was recognised with the Gold Bear award for direction and Silver Bear for DiCaprio's performance. Luhrmann also produced both volumes of the soundtrack album, which went triple-platinum.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chagollan |first1=Steve |title='Gatsby's' Great Music Collection |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/features/gatsby-1200370682/ |website=Variety |publisher=Penske Business Media, LLC |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nLuhrmann's Oscar-winning musical ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'' (2001), set in the Montmartre Quarter of Paris at the dawn of the 20th century, told the story of a young English poet/writer, Christian ([[Ewan McGregor]]) who falls in love with the star of the Moulin Rouge, cabaret actress and courtesan Satine ([[Nicole Kidman]]). The film was praised by its adherents, including famed musical directors [[Robert Wise]] and [[Stanley Donen]], as having re-invented the modern musical, blending decades of popular music in remixes and mash-ups.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Berk |first1=Philip |title=2002 \u2013 Musical or Comedy: ''Moulin Rouge!''|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/articles/2002-musical-or-comedy-moulin-rouge |website=Golden Globe Awards |publisher=HFPA |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> The movie was named one of the AFI's top ten films of 2001<ref>{{cite web |title=American Film Institute's Top Films of the Year|url=http://www.infoplease.com/ipea/A0878236.html|work=InfoPlease|accessdate=28 June 2011}}</ref> and in 2010 was chosen as the top film of the 2000s decade in a poll of 150,000 respondents in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|title=Moulin Rouge! voted best film of the decade|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/film-news/6944981/NEEDS-PIC-Moulin-Rouge-voted-best-film-of-the-decade.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=7 January 2010|accessdate=28 June 2011|location=London}}</ref> At the 59th Annual Golden Globes, Moulin Rouge! took home the awards for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress]], and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Winners & Nominees 2002 |url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2002 |website=Golden Globe Awards |publisher=HFPA |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> The film also gave birth to a successful soundtrack album, produced by Luhrmann, which sold more than seven million copies and went double-platinum, led by the Grammy-winning number one hit single \"[[Lady Marmalade]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Lady Marmalade Wins Grammy Award|url=http://www.bignoisenow.com/christina/grammy02win.html|publisher=BigNoiseNow|date=28 February 2002|accessdate=28 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Chagollan |first1=Steve |title='Gatsby's' Great Music Collection |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/features/gatsby-1200370682/ |website=Variety |publisher=Penske Business Media |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nLuhrmann's 2008 historical epic ''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]'' featured some of the country's most celebrated actors, including [[Nicole Kidman]], [[Hugh Jackman]], and [[David Gulpilil]]. Situated between the two World Wars, the film blended a nostalgic romance with major events from Australian history, including the [[Bombing of Darwin]], and the true story of the [[Stolen Generations]], wherein thousands of mixed-race Aboriginal children were stolen from their families by the state and forcibly integrated into white society. The movie's racial politics were controversial for their time, and notably, its production coincided with Prime Minister Kevin Rudd's 2008 [[Apology to Australia's Indigenous peoples]]. [[Marcia Langton]], professor of Australian indigenous studies at [[University of Melbourne|Melbourne University]] publicly supported the film, saying \"Luhrmann depicts with satirical sharpness the racial caste system of that time... In his imagined cinema of the 1940s, the spatial and social shape of racism is reconstructed with such exact detail, I felt I had been transported back to my own childhood.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Langton |first1=Marcia |title=Faraway Downs fantasy resonates close to home |url=https://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/faraway-downs-fantasy-resonates-close-to-home-20081123-ge7jaa.html |website=The Age |accessdate=7 March 2019}}</ref> While achieving modest box office success in the United States, the film was very successful in Europe, maintaining the #1 slot at the box office for many weeks in France, Germany, Spain, Italy and the Scandinavian countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=australia.htm|website=Box Office Mojo|title=Australia|accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> It is the second-highest grossing Australian film of all time, next to ''[[Crocodile Dundee]]'' and ahead of ''[[Happy Feet]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Highest Grossing Aussie Films|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/1009915/highest-grossing-aussie-films|work=World News Australia|publisher=Published by SBS|date=27 February 2009|accessdate=28 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Luhrmann [[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|adapted]] F. Scott Fitzgerald's ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'', shot in 3D,<ref>{{cite news|title=Baz Luhrmann eyes ''Great Gatsby''|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117997638.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=Michael Jones|date=18 December 2008|accessdate=11 August 2009}}</ref> starring [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] as [[Jay Gatsby]], [[Tobey Maguire]] as [[Nick Carraway]], [[Carey Mulligan]] as [[Daisy Buchanan]], [[Joel Edgerton]] as Tom Buchanan, Australian newcomer [[Elizabeth Debicki]] as Jordan Baker, and legendary Indian actor [[Amitabh Bachchan]] as Meyer Wolfsheim. For the film, Luhrmann and costume/production designer Catherine Martin collaborated with [[Prada]], [[Brooks Brothers]], and [[Tiffany & Co]] to create period-inspired dresses, suits, and jewelry based on their own archives and true to the book's own references to luxury brands.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Lucie |title=Luxury brands and 'The Great Gatsby' movie |url=https://www.ft.com/content/c8098b7e-ace8-11e2-b27f-00144feabdc0 |website=Financial Times |publisher=The Financial Times LTD |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> The film grossed over $353 million worldwide, making it the director's highest-grossing movie to date.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Great Gatsby |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=greatgatsby2012.htm |website=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Baz Luhrmann |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Director&id=bazluhrmann.htm |website=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> Critic Richard Roeper described the adaptation as \"the best attempt yet to capture the essence of the novel\u201d while Fitzgerald's granddaughter praised the movie, saying \"Scott would have been proud.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Roeper |first1=Richard |title=The Great Gatsby |url=http://www.richardroeper.com/reviews/thegreatgatsby.aspx |website=RichardRoeper.com |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kendall |first1=Mary Claire |title=\"Loving 'Gatsby' All About 'Living Fitzgerald'\" |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maryclairekendall/2013/05/10/loving-gatsby-all-about-living-fitzgerald/#3dd5537a611f |website=Forbes |publisher=Forbes Media LLC |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> The following year, at the [[86th Academy Awards]], the film won in both of its nominated categories: [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]] and [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The 86th Academy Awards \u2013 2014|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2014 |website=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> The soundtrack, produced by Luhrmann, Anton Monsted, and [[Jay-Z]], sought to blend the music of the Jazz Age with contemporary hip-hop as two historical analogues.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Young |first1=Alex |title=The Great Gatsby soundtrack features new Jay-Z, The xx, Florence & the Machine |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2013/04/the-great-gatsby-soundtrack-features-new-jay-z-the-xx-florence-the-machine/ |website=Consequence of Sound |publisher=Consequence of Sound |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> Featured artists included [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Jack White]], [[Lana Del Rey]], [[Sia (musician)|Sia]], [[will.i.am]], [[The xx]], and [[Florence and the Machine]]; the soundtrack also included score from the film's composer and Luhrmann's repeat collaborator [[Craig Armstrong (composer)|Craig Armstrong]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blistein |first1=Jon |title='Great Gatsby' Soundtrack Featured Jay-Z, Andre 3000, Beyonce |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/great-gatsby-soundtrack-features-jay-z-andre-3000-beyonce-186765/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> The album's sales exceeded expectations, marking the biggest digital sales week for a soundtrack in Billboard history, and peaking at number one on the US Billboard 200 chart.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Corner |first1=Lewis |title='Great Gatsby', Lady Antebellum storm US album chart |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/music/a481948/great-gatsby-lady-antebellum-storm-us-album-chart/ |website=Digital Spy |publisher=National Magazine Company, Ltd. |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Soundtrack Chart History |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/soundtrack/chart-history/alternative-albums |website=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media, LLC |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nLuhrmann is currently in pre-production for a film about [[Elvis Presley]]'s relationship with [[Colonel Tom Parker]], set to start filming in February 2020 and due to be released in October 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/dune-baz-luhrmann-elvis-presley-movie-release-dates-1202660346/|title=Warner Bros. Dates Baz Luhrmann \u2018Elvis Presley\u2019 Movie, Shifts \u2018Dune\u2019 & More|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-08-02|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref> In March 2018, it was announced that [[Tom Hanks]] would play Parker and later in July, news broke that [[Austin Butler]] had been cast as the famed singer after a series of screen tests, as well as music and performance workshops.<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/07/elvis-presley-movie-baz-luhrmann-ansel-elgort-miles-teller-austin-butler-harry-styles-tom-hanks-1202640766/</ref><ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/harry-styles-ansel-elgort-miles-teller-running-play-elvis-baz-luhrmann-film-1222173</ref><ref>https://news.avclub.com/baz-luhrmanns-elvis-biopic-finds-its-star-austin-butle-1836382932</ref>\n\n==Television==\n[[File:Baz Luhrmann Cannes 2013.jpg|thumb|upright|Luhrmann at the [[2013 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\nIn 2016, Luhrmann collaborated with award-winning playwright [[Stephen Adly Guirgis]] on the [[Netflix]] series ''[[The Get Down]]'' about the birth of [[hip-hop]] in the 1970s.<ref>Hetrick, Adam. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/baz-luhrmann-and-stephen-adly-guirgis-collaborating-on-hip-hop-television-p-212833 \"Baz Luhrmann and Stephen Adly Guirgis Collaborating on Hip-Hop Television Project\"]. ''[[Playbill]]'', December 13, 2013</ref> For the series, Luhrmann brought on [[Nas]], [[Grandmaster Flash]], [[Kurtis Blow]] and [[DJ Kool Herc]] as producers, to help tell the story of the rise of hip hop, punk, and disco during shifting cultural and political transformation through his unique brand of magical realism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/1263-netflixs-the-get-down-is-the-rare-and-great-music-drama-thats-actually-about-music/|title=Netflix\u2019s \"The Get Down\" Is the Rare (And Great) Music Drama That\u2019s Actually About Music|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> The series featured two parts, praised for its vibrant music, fresh cast and authenticity, due to the involvement of many of the era's key historical figures in central roles to the show's development.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Get Down|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_get_down|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> Part One was certified fresh by [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with a score of 77%, while Part Two of the series holds a critic score of 86%.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Get Down: Season One |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_get_down/s01 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Get Down: Season Two |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_get_down/s02 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Acting and director credits==\n\n===Director credits===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Film\n! Year\n! Awards\n|-\n| ''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n|1992\n| [[Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts|AFI Award]] for Best Director<br/>AFI Award for Best Screenplay<br/>[[London Critics Circle Film Awards|ALFS Award]] for Newcomer of the Year<br/>Nominated\u2014[[BAFTA Film Award]] for Best Adapted Screenplay<br/>Nominated\u201420/20 Award for Best Original Screenplay\n|-\n|''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''\n|1996\n| [[51st British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Award]] for [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]<br/>BAFTA Award for [[BAFTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[Berlin International Film Festival|Golden Bear Award]] for Best Picture\n|-\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|2001\n| [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]<br/>[[National Board of Review|National Board of Review Award]] for [[National Board of Review Award for Best Film|Best Film]]<br/>[[Producers Guild of America Award]] for Best Picture<br/>[[Satellite Award]] for [[Satellite Award for Best Director|Best Director]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[AACTA Award]] for [[AACTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]<br/>Nominated\u2014AACTA Award for [[AACTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Award]] for [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]<br/>Nominated\u2014BAFTA Award for [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]<br/>Nominated\u2014BAFTA Award for [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]<br/>Nominated\u2014Golden Globe for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director|Best Director]]<br/>Nominated\u2014Satellite Award for [[Satellite Award for Best Film|Best Film]]<br/>Nominated\u2014Satellite Award for [[Satellite Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]\n|-\n|''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]''\n|2008\n| Nominated\u2014[[Satellite Award]] for [[Satellite Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[AACTA Awards|AFI]] [[AFI Members' Choice Award|Members' Choice Award]]\n|-\n|''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]''\n|2013\n| [[AACTA Awards|AACTA Award]] for [[AACTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]<br/>AACTA Award for [[AACTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]<br/>AACTA Award for [[AACTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[AACTA Awards|AACTA International Award]] for [[AACTA International Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association|Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Award]] for [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n|-\n| ''[[Elvis (2021 film)|Elvis]]''\n|2021\n|\n|}\n\n===Creator===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Film\n! Year\n! Notes\n|-\n|''[[The Get Down]]''\n|2016\u20132017\n|Streaming on [[Netflix]]\n|}\n\n===Screen actor===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Film\n! Year\n! Character\n! Notes\n|-\n| ''[[A Country Practice]]'' (TV) || 1981\u201382 || Jerry Percival || Guest star for six episodes.\n|-\n| ''[[Winter of Our Dreams]]'' (film) || 1981 || Pete || Also starred [[Judy Davis]] and [[Bryan Brown]].\n|-\n| ''[[The Dark Room (1982 film)|The Bedroom]]'' (film) || 1982 || First student || Small role.\n|-\n| ''[[The Highest Honor]]'' (film) || 1982 || Able Seaman A. W. Huston || Also starred [[Steve Bisley]].\n|-\n| ''Kids of the Cross'' (TV documentary) || 1983 || Himself || Filmed in Sydney in 1981. Produced by [[Mike Willesee]].\n|}\n\n===Stage actor===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Name\n! Year\n! Character\n! Notes\n|-\n| ''Are You Lonesome Tonight?'' || 1982 || Unknown || Performed at Nimrod Downstairs, Sydney. Directed by Peter Kingston.\n|-\n| ''Fanshen'' || 1983 || Peasant || Performed at [[National Institute of Dramatic Art|NIDA]], Sydney.\n|-\n| ''[[Summerfolk|Holiday Makers]]'' || 1984 || Unknown || Performed at NIDA. Directed by [[Nick Enright]].\n|-\n| ''[[All's Well That Ends Well]]'' || 1984 || Dumain Brother || Performed at NIDA. Directed by Kevin Jackson.\n|-\n| ''[[Strictly Ballroom]]'' || 1984; 1986 || Ross Pierce || Performed at NIDA in 1984, and in [[Bratislava]] in 1986; also directed.\n|-\n| ''[[A Dream Play|Dreamplay]]'' || 1985 || Unknown || Performed at NIDA. Directed by [[Jim Sharman]].\n|-\n| ''[[Funeral Games (play)|Funeral Games]]'' || 1985 || Unknown || Part of the ''Hallucinogenics? 3 plays from the 60s'' event. Performed at NIDA. Directed by Egil Kipste.\n|-\n| ''[[Chamber Music (play)|Chamber Music]]'' || 1985 || Unknown || Part of the ''Hallucinogenics? 3 plays from the 60s'' event. Performed at NIDA. Directed by Ros Horin.\n|-\n| ''The Greeks'' || 1985 || Unknown || Trilogy: ''The War'', ''The Murders'', ''The Gods''. Performed at NIDA, and St Martin's Youth Arts Centre, [[Melbourne]].\n|-\n| ''[[Once in a Lifetime (play)|Once in a Lifetime]]'' || 1985 || Unknown || Performed at NIDA. Directed by [[Gale Edwards]].\n|-\n| ''Crocodile Creek'' || 1986 || \u2013 || Directed for the New Moon Theatre Company in [[Rockhampton]]. Amateur musical production set in the Queensland goldfields.\n|-\n| ''The Conquest of the South Pole'' || 1989 || Unknown || Performed at [[Belvoir St Theatre]], Sydney. Directed by [[Jim Sharman]].\n|}\n\n==Other work==\n{{prose|section|date=October 2019}}\n*'''1981:''' A young Luhrmann can be seen in an early acting role in the film ''[[Winter of Our Dreams]]'', directed by [[John Duigan]]. Luhrmann has a small part playing opposite [[Judy Davis]].\n*'''1992:''' Luhrmann directed a video for [[John Paul Young]]'s \"Love Is in the Air\", which was rereleased to coincide with the release of ''Strictly Ballroom'' in which the song was featured prominently.\n*'''1993:''' Luhrmann staged his interpretation of [[Benjamin Britten]]'s version of ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream (opera)|A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'', set in colonial India, for the [[Australian Opera]]. After successful seasons in Sydney and Melbourne, the production went on to win the Critics' Prize at the [[Edinburgh Festival]]. Music extracts can be heard on his album ''[[Something for Everybody (Baz Luhrmann album)|Something for Everybody]]''.\n*'''1993:''' Luhrmann assisted in the election campaign of former Australian prime minister [[Paul Keating]].\n*'''1997:''' The CD of ''Something for Everybody'' was released, featuring music from Luhrmann's films and operas including his version of Britten's ''A Midsummer Night's Dream''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/release/1255770|title=Bazmark Inc. Presents Something For Everybody (CD, Comp)|work=Discogs}}</ref> Moreover, Luhrmann created his own company with his wife [[Catherine Martin (designer)|Catherine Martin]]: {{ill|Bazmark|fr}}.\n*'''1999:''' As a music producer, Luhrmann is credited with \"[[Everybody's Free (To Wear Sunscreen)]]\", a successful [[spoken word]] song in Europe and the Americas.\n*'''2002:''' Luhrmann brought his production of [[Giacomo Puccini|Puccini]]'s ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' to the [[Broadway Theatre (53rd Street)|Broadway Theatre]] in New York City. Originally produced for [[Opera Australia]] in Sydney in 1990, once in New York it eventually received seven [[Tony Award]] nominations, including Best Revival of a Musical, Best Direction (Luhrmann), Best Orchestrations (Nicholas Kitsopoulos), Best Costume Design (Catherine Martin), and winning Best Set Design (Catherine Martin), Best Lighting Design (Nigel Levings), and the [[Tony Honors for Excellence in Theatre]] for the Principal Ensemble Cast.\n*'''2004:''' Luhrmann directed a lavish multimillion-dollar commercial for [[Chanel N\u00b0 5]] titled ''[[No. 5 the Film|N\u00b0 5 the Film]]'', inspired by his Red Curtain trilogy, starring Nicole Kidman and [[Rodrigo Santoro]]. On the ''[[Charlie Rose (TV series)|Charlie Rose]]'' interview show he told Rose that he based the commercial on the 1953 film ''[[Roman Holiday]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlierose.com/view/interview/9669 |title=Charlie Rose \u2013 A conversation about the film \"Australia\" |author=Luhrmann, Baz |work=[[The Charlie Rose Show]] |date=27 November 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402111603/http://www.charlierose.com/view/interview/9669 |archivedate=2 April 2015 }}</ref>\n*'''2005:''' Luhrmann was appointed an Ambassador for the [[Australian Theatre for Young People]].\n*'''2008:''' Luhrmann was asked by the Prime Minister of Australia [[Kevin Rudd]] to make new advertisements to promote Australia as a tourist destination.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601081&sid=aqTdor3btTDI|title=Australia Taps Luhrmann for Campaign to Boost Tourism|first=Malcolm|last=Scott|publisher=Bloomberg.com|date=29 July 2008}}</ref>\n*'''2009:''' At the [[81st Academy Awards]] in February, Luhrmann put together a number dedicated to musicals which consisted of [[Hugh Jackman]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Zac Efron]], [[Vanessa Hudgens]], [[Dominic Cooper]] and [[Amanda Seyfried]].\n*'''2009:''' In September, Luhrmann made an appearance as a guest judge on ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 9)|Dancing with the Stars]]''.\n*'''2010:''' Luhrmann and the painter Vincent Fantauzzo embarked on an art initiative which took them to India, where they created artworks on walls of hotels, in the streets of Rajasthan and on 17th century forts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnngo.com/mumbai/play/baz-luhrmann-vincent-fantauzzos-mad-indian-motorcycle-diary-016354|title=Baz Luhrmann & Vincent Fantauzzo's mad Indian motorcycle diary|author=Kanwardeep Singh Dhaliwal|publisher=CNNgo.com|date=24 March 2010|access-date=27 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114134252/http://www.cnngo.com/mumbai/play/baz-luhrmann-vincent-fantauzzos-mad-indian-motorcycle-diary-016354|archive-date=14 January 2012|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n*'''2017:''' Luhrmann shot the campaign film ''The Secret Life of Flowers'' for the collaboration between [[Erdem Moral\u0131o\u011flu|Erdem]] and [[H&M]].<ref>{{YouTube|PEANC3ipyws|ERDEM x H&M \u2013 ''The Secret Life of Flowers'' campaign film by Baz Luhrmann}}</ref>\n*'''2019:''' Though mostly hands-off with the stage production of [[Moulin Rouge! (musical)|''Moulin Rouge!'' (musical)]], Luhrmann produced its Broadway cast recording.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/09/02/baz-luhrmanns-moulin-rouge-mega-mashup|title=Baz Luhrmann\u2019s \"Moulin Rouge!\" Mega Mashup|last=Schulman|first=Michael|date=2019-08-26|access-date=2019-10-22|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n\n==Collaborations==\nLuhrmann has cast certain actors in more than one of his films:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!\n! ''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n! ''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''\n! ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n! ''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]''\n!''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]''\n|-\n|Veronica Beattie\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Max Cullen]]\n|\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Leonardo DiCaprio]]\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Arthur Dignam]]\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|Steven Grace\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Nigel Harbach\n|\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|Michelle Hopper\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Bill Hunter (actor)|Bill Hunter]]\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|-\n|[[Nicole Kidman]]\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|-\n|[[Jacek Koman]]\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[John Leguizamo]]\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Tara Morice]]\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Lara Mulcahy\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Barry Otto]]\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|John Sheerin\n|\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Jack Thompson (actor)|Jack Thompson]]\n|\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Kerry Walker]]\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|-\n|[[David Wenham]]\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|-\n|[[Peter Whitford]]\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Matthew Whittet\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|}\n\n==Influences==\nLuhrmann has cited [[Grand opera#Italy|Italian grand opera]] as a major influence on his work and has also given a nod to other theatrical styles, such as [[Bollywood]] films, as having influenced his style. Luhrmann was a ballroom dancer as a child and his mother taught ballroom dancing which was an inspiration for ''Strictly Ballroom''. Luhrmann's favourite films are ''[[Star 80]]'', ''[[8\u00bd]]'', ''[[War and Peace (film series)|War and Peace]]'', ''[[Medium Cool]]'' and ''[[Fitzcarraldo]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/william_shakespeares_romeo_and_juliet/news/1921010/five_favorite_films_with_baz_luhrmann|title=Five Favorite Films of Baz Luhrmann}} Rotten Tomatoes. 19 October 2010. Retrieved 29 March 2013.</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n\n=== AACTA Awards ===\nLuhrmann has received four awards from nine  [[AACTA Awards|Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts Awards]] nominations.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n|Best Director\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":0\">{{IMDb title|id=0105488|title=Strictly Ballroom|section=awards}}</ref>\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n|Best Screenplay, Original or Adapted\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''\n|Best Foreign Film\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":1\">{{IMDb title|id=0117509|title=Romeo + Juliet|section=awards}}</ref>\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Direction\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\">{{IMDb title|id=0203009|title=Moulin Rouge!|section=awards}}</ref>\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Film\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]''\n|Best Original Score\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":3\">{{IMDb title|id=0455824|title=Australia|section=awards}}</ref>\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]''\n|News Limited Readers' Choice Award\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|[[3rd AACTA Awards|2014]]\n|''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]''\n|Best Direction\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":4\">{{IMDb title|id=1343092|title=The Great Gatsby|section=awards}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[3rd AACTA Awards|2014]]\n|''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]''\n|Best Film\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":4\" />\n|}\n\n=== Academy Awards ===\n''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'' was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] at the [[74th Academy Awards]]. Luhrmann was not nominated for Best Director, prompting host [[Whoopi Goldberg]] to remark, \"I guess [it] just directed itself.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/oscar-insanity-132261|title=Oscar Insanity|date=2003-03-11|work=Newsweek|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|[[74th Academy Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Picture\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|}\n\n=== British Academy Film Awards ===\nLuhrmann has received two awards from seven [[British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Award]] nominations.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|[[46th British Academy Film Awards|1993]]\n|''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n|Best Screenplay, Adapted\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[46th British Academy Film Awards|1993]]\n|''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n|Best Film\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[51st British Academy Film Awards|1998]]\n|''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''\n|Best Screenplay, Adapted\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[51st British Academy Film Awards|1998]]\n|''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''\n|David Lean Award for Direction\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[55th British Academy Film Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Screenplay\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|[[55th British Academy Film Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|David Lean Award for Direction\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|[[55th British Academy Film Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Film\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|}\n\n=== Golden Globe Awards ===\nLuhrmann has been nominated three times for [[Golden Globe Award]]s, winning in 2002 for Best Motion Picture, Comedy or Musical\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|[[51st Golden Globe Awards|1994]]\n|''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n|Best Motion Picture, Comedy or Musical\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[59th Golden Globe Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Motion Picture, Comedy or Musical\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|[[59th Golden Globe Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Director, Motion Picture\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|}\n\n=== Grammy Awards ===\nLuhrmann has been specifically been nominated three times for [[Grammy Award]]s, with additional accolades for songs on the albums he has produced for his films, including wins for [[Lady Marmalade]] at [[44th Annual Grammy Awards|2002's Grammy's]] ([[Grammy Award for Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals]]), as well as nominations for [[Young and Beautiful (Lana Del Rey song)]] for the [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media]] the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards|2014 Grammy's]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|[[44th Annual Grammy Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge! Music from Baz Luhrmann's Film]]''\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[56th Annual Grammy Awards|2014]]\n|''[[The Great Gatsby: Music from Baz Luhrmann's Film]]''\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|-\n|[[62nd Annual Grammy Awards|2020]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge! (musical)|Moulin Rouge! The Musical]]'' Original Broadway Cast Recording\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album|Best Musical Theater Album]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|}\n\n=== Tony Awards ===\nLuhrmann has specifically been nominated for two [[Tony Award]]s, and his production of ''[[La boh\u00e8me#Modernizations|La Boheme]]'' also won awards for Best Scenic Design and Best Lighting Design at the [[57th Tony Awards]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|2003\n|[[La boh\u00e8me#Modernizations|''La boh\u00e8me'']]\n|Best Direction in a Musical\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":5\">{{IBDB title|id=13346#awards|title=La Boh\u00e8me}}</ref>\n|-\n|2003\n|[[La boh\u00e8me#Modernizations|''La boh\u00e8me'']]\n|Best Revival of a Musical\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":5\" />\n|}\n\n=== Additional awards ===\n*[[American Film Institute#AFI Awards|AFI Awards]], USA \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, AFI Film Award; AFI Movie of the Year for ''Moulin Rouge''\n*[[Australians in Film]] \u2013\n**2013 \u2013 Won, Orry-Kelly International Award Honoree\n*[[47th Berlin International Film Festival|Berlin International Film Festival]] \u2013 1997 \u2013 Won, [[Alfred Bauer Prize]] for ''William Shakespeare's Romeo + Juliet''; Nominated, Golden Berlin Bear for ''William Shakespeare's Romeo + Juliet''<ref name=\"Berlinale 1997\">{{cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1997/03_preistr_ger_1997/03_Preistraeger_1997.html|title=Berlinale: 1997 Prize Winners|accessdate=12 January 2012|work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n*[[Bodil Awards]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, Bodil, Best Non-American Film (Bedste ikke amerikanske film) for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*Bogota Film Festival \u2013 1994 \u2013 Nominated, Golden Precolumbian Circle. Best Film for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*[[Broadcast Film Critics Association Awards]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Won, Critics Choice Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Cannes Film Festival]] \u2013\n**2001 \u2013 Nominated, Palme d'Or for ''Moulin Rouge!'';\n**1992 \u2013 Won, Award of the Youth, Foreign Film for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*[[Chicago Film Critics Association Awards]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, CFCA Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Clio Awards]] \u2013  2016 \u2013  Won, Honorary Award<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://clios.com/news/2016-honorary-award-recipient-baz-luhrmann|title=2016 Honorary Award Recipient: Baz Luhrmann|date=2016-09-26|work=Clios|access-date=2018-01-31|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*[[C\u00e9sar Awards]], France \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, C\u00e9sar, Best Foreign Film (Meilleur film \u00e9tranger) for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Drama Desk Award]]  \u2013  2003  \u2013  Nominated, Outstanding Revival of a Musical and Best Direction for [[La boh\u00e8me#Modernizations|''La Boheme'']]<ref name=\":5\" />\n*[[Directors Guild of America]], USA \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, DGA Award, Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Motion Pictures for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Empire Awards]], UK \u2013 2002 \u2013 Won, Empire Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[European Film Awards]] \u2013\n**2001 \u2013 Won, Screen International Award for ''Moulin Rouge!'';\n**1997 \u2013 Nominated, Screen International Award for ''William Shakespeare's Romeo + Juliet''\n*[[Film Critics Circle of Australia Awards]] \u2013\n**2009 \u2013 Nominated, FCCA Award, Best Film for ''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]'';\n**2002 \u2013 Won, FCCA Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''; Nominated, FCCA Award, Best Screenplay \u2013 Original for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Hollywood Film Festival]] \u2013 2001 \u2013 Won, Hollywood Movie of the Year for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Inside Film Awards]] \u2013 2001 \u2013 Nominated, Best Feature Film for ''Moulin Rouge!''; Nominated, Best Direction for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Italian National Syndicate of Film Journalists]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, Silver Ribbon, Best Director \u2013 Foreign Film (Regista del Miglior Film Straniero) for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[London Critics Circle Film Awards]] \u2013\n**1998 \u2013 Nominated, ALFS Award, Director of the Year for ''William Shakespeare's Romeo + Juliet'';\n**1993 \u2013 Won, ALFS Award, Newcomer of the Year for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*Love is Folly International Film Festival, Bulgaria \u2013 1993 \u2013 Won, Golden Aphrodite for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*[[MTV Movie & TV Awards]] \u2013 1997 \u2013 Nominated, Best Movie for [[Romeo + Juliet]]\n*[[Online Film Critics Society Awards]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, OFCS Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Producers Guild of America Award]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Won, Motion Picture Producer of the Year Award for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Palm Springs International Film Festival]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Won, Sonny Bono Visionary Award\n*Phoenix Film Critics Society Awards \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, PFCS Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*Robert Festival \u2013\n**2002 \u2013 Won, Robert, Best Non-American Film (\u00c5rets ikke-amerikanske film) for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n**1993 \u2013 Won, Robert, Best Foreign Film (\u00c5rets udenlandske spillefilm) for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*[[Satellite Awards]] \u2013\n**2008 \u2013 Won, Auteur Award, Nominated, Satellite Award, Best Screenplay, Original for ''Australia''; Nominated, Satellite Award, Best Original Song for ''Australia'' for the song \"By the Boab Tree\";\n**2002 \u2013 Won, Golden Satellite Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''. Nominated, Golden Satellite Award, Best Screenplay, Original for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Teen Choice Awards]] \u2013 \n**2002 \u2013 Nominated, Film \u2013 Choice Movie, Drama/Action/Adventure for ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n**2009 \u2013 Nominated, Film \u2013 Choice Movie, Romance for ''[[Australia (2008 film)]]''\n*[[Toronto International Film Festival]] \u2013 1992 \u2013 Won, People's Choice Award for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*[[Vancouver Film Critics Circle]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Won, VFCC Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Vancouver International Film Festival]] \u2013 1992 \u2013 Won, Most Popular Film for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*World Soundtrack Awards \u2013 2001 \u2013 Won, World Soundtrack Award, Most Creative Use of Existing Material on a Soundtrack for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Writers Guild of America Award]], USA \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, WGA Award (Screen), Best Screenplay Written Directly for the Screen for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n\n== Media appearances ==\n*In September 2009, Luhrmann made an appearance as a guest judge on ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 9)|Dancing with the Stars]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Baz Luhrmann Guest Judges On ''Dancing''|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/09/28/baz-luhrmann-guest-judges_n_302461.html|accessdate=6 February 2014|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=28 September 2009}}</ref> Luhrmann participated on the [[NPR]] radio quiz program ''[[Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]'' in 2013.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2013/09/07/219704753/not-my-job-we-ask-australian-baz-luhrmann-about-austria ''Wait Wait...Don't Tell Me!''] from [[National Public Radio|NPR]]</ref>\n*Luhrmann's song \"Everybody's Free (To Wear Sunscreen)\" was discussed in March 2020 on the [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] ''[[Adrian Chiles|Chiles on Friday]]'' programme with Charlotte McDonald. It featured an interview from the documentary with Australian voice over artist, [[Lee Perry (voice actor)|Lee Perry]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w3cszvtr \"The Sunscreen Song; The Class of '99\"], [[BBC World Service]]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Baz Luhrmann}}\n* {{official website|http://www.bazmark.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|525303}}\n\n{{Baz Luhrmann}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Baz Luhrmann\n| list =\n{{AACTA Award Best Direction}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Direction 1985\u20132009}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay 1983\u20131999}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Director}}\n{{Empire Award for Best Director}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Director}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luhrmann, Baz}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:ARIA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Australian film directors]]\n[[Category:Australian opera directors]]\n[[Category:Australian film producers]]\n[[Category:Australian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Australian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Best Director BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Director Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:European Film Awards winners (people)]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:National Institute of Dramatic Art alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Sydney]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian director, writer, and producer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Baz Luhrmann\n| image              = Baz Luhrmann.jpg\n| caption            = Luhrmann in 2013\n| birth_name         = Mark Anthony Luhrmann\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1962|9|17}}\n| birth_place        = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia<ref>{{cite web |url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800026871/bio|title=Baz Luhrmann biodata|work=Yahoo! Movies|accessdate=14 November 2009}}</ref>\n| alma_mater         = [[Narrabeen Sports High School]]\n| occupation         = Film director, screenwriter, producer, actor\n| years_active       = 1982\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Catherine Martin (designer)|Catherine Martin]]|1997}}\n| children           = 2\n}}\n\n'''Baz Luhrmann''' (born '''Mark Anthony Luhrmann''', 17 September 1962) is an Australian director, writer, and producer with projects spanning film, television, opera, theatre, music, and recording industries. He is regarded by many as a contemporary example of an [[auteur]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/09/magazine/deep-inside-baz-luhrmanns-creative-chaos.html|title=Deep Inside Baz Luhrmann's Creative Chaos|last=Wallace|first=Amy|date=2014-02-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-25|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> for his style and deep involvement in the writing, directing, design, and musical components of all his work. He is the most commercially successful Australian director, with four of his films in the top ten highest worldwide grossing [[Australian films]] of all time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-08-01/top-10-australian-films-at-australian-box-office/6655808|title=Top 10 grossing Australian films of all time|date=2015-08-01|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/entertainment/movies/2016/12/30/best-australian-movies/|title=Australia's top 10 highest grossing films of all time|date=2016-12-30|work=The New Daily|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn the screen he is best known for his \"Red Curtain Trilogy,\" comprising his romantic comedy film ''[[Strictly Ballroom]]'' (1992), the romantic tragedy ''[[Romeo + Juliet|William Shakespeare's Romeo + Juliet]]'' (1996), and ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'' (2001). Following the trilogy, projects included ''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]'' (2008), ''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]'' (2013), and his television period drama ''[[The Get Down]]'' for [[Netflix]]. Additional projects include stage productions of [[Giacomo Puccini]]'s ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' for both the [[Australian Opera]] and [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] and ''[[Strictly Ballroom (musical)|Strictly Ballroom the Musical]]''.\n\nLuhrmann is equally known for his [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-nominated soundtracks for ''[[Moulin Rouge! Music from Baz Luhrmann's Film|Moulin Rouge!]]'' and [[The Great Gatsby: Music from Baz Luhrmann's Film|''The Great Gatsby'']], as well as his record label House of Iona, a co-venture with [[RCA Records]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6473231/baz-luhrmann-rca-to-launch-bazmark-label|title=Baz Luhrmann, RCA To Launch Bazmark Label|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-07-05}}</ref> Serving as producer on all of his musical soundtracks, he also holds writing credits on many of the individual tracks. His album ''[[Something for Everybody (Baz Luhrmann album)|Something For Everybody]]'' features music from many of his films and also includes his hit \"[[Everybody's Free (To Wear Sunscreen)]]\".\n\nLuhrmann's influence has extended outside the traditional realm of media and entertainment. Deeply involved in the fashion and art worlds, Luhrmann's ''[[No. 5 the Film]]'' for [[Chanel]] not only holds a [[Guinness World Records|Guinness World Record]] for the highest budget for an advertising commercial ever produced,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-expensive-advertisement-(commercial)-on-television/|title=Most expensive advertisement (commercial) on television|work=Guinness World Records|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> but pioneered the now commonplace genre of fashion film and [[branded content]]. Luhrmann works closely with the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]]'s [[Anna Wintour Costume Center]], having chaired the annual [[Met Gala]] as well as producing a short film for the museum, celebrating [[Miuccia Prada]] and [[Elsa Schiaparelli]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/exhibitions/listings/2012/impossible-conversations/audio-and-video|title=Audio and Video {{!}} The Metropolitan Museum of Art|website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2018-01-25}}</ref> More recently he and his wife [[Catherine Martin (designer)|Catherine Martin]] have adapted their style for projects in events, retail, architecture and design with [[Barneys New York]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/baz-dazzled-barneys-new-york-holiday-windows-unveiling|title=Baz Dazzled: The Barneys New York Holiday Window Unveiling with Baz Luhrmann and Catherine Martin|work=Vogue|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en}}</ref> and developer and hotelier [[Alan Faena]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/what-looks-like-baz-luhrmann-838537|title=What It Looks Like When Baz Luhrmann Helps Design a Miami Hotel|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/annabel/2016/05/11/the-maestro-of-miami-beach-alan-faena-and-his-new-faena-hotel/|title=The Maestro of Miami Beach: Alan Faena and His New Faena Hotel|last=Abel|first=Ann|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-01-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLuhrmann was born in Sydney. His mother, Barbara Carmel (n\u00e9e Brennan), was a ballroom dance teacher and dress shop owner, and his father, Leonard Luhrmann, ran a petrol station and a movie theatre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/28/Baz-Luhrmann.html|title=Baz Luhrmann profile at|work=FilmReference.com}}</ref><ref>[http://www.couriermail.com.au/entertainment/movies/man-of-many-talents/story-e6freqex-1111118148222 \"Baz Luhrmann a man of many talents\"], ''[[The Courier-Mail]]'', 26 November 2008</ref><ref>[http://familytreemaker.genealogy.com/users/h/a/r/Jennifer-Harrison-Chisholm/WEBSITE-0001/UHP-0318.html Luhrmann-related genealogy site]</ref> He was raised in [[Herons Creek, New South Wales|Herons Creek]], a tiny rural settlement in northern [[New South Wales]]. He attended St&nbsp;Joseph's Hastings Regional School, [[Port Macquarie]] (1975\u20131978); [[St Paul's College, Manly|St Paul's Catholic College]], performing in the school's version of Shakespeare's ''[[Henry IV, Part 1]]'', and [[Narrabeen Sports High School]], where he met future collaborator [[Craig Pearce]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8P8aBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT14&q=Craig%20Pearce%20narrabeen%20sports%20high%20school|title=Baz Luhrmann: Interviews|last=Ryan|first=Tom|date=2014-11-05|publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi|isbn=9781626743007|language=en}}</ref>\n\nLuhrmann received the nickname \"Baz\" from his father, given to him because of his afro hair style, the name coming from the English [[Basil Brush]]. While still in high school, Luhrmann changed his name by deed poll to Bazmark, joining his nickname and birth name together.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/apr/23/baz-luhrmann-strictly-ballroom-the-musical-interview \"Baz Luhrmann: 'I've never waited for permission to do anything'&thinsp;\"] by Ryan Gilbey, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 24 April 2018</ref> In 1980 Luhrmann graduated high school and in the same year was cast opposite [[Judy Davis]] in the Australian film ''[[Winter of Our Dreams]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baz Luhrmann i(10 works by) (birth name: Mark Anthony Luhrmann) (a.k.a. Bazmark Anthony Luhrmann)|url=http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/OLD?id=A3x&idtype=oldid|work=AustLit|publisher=AustLit|accessdate=6 February 2014|year=2014}}</ref> In 1982 using the money he had earned from film and television experience he funded his own theatre company, The Bond Theatre Company, with future friends and collaborators Nelly Hooper and Gabrielle Mason. The company performed at [[Bondi Pavilion|the Pavilion at Sydney's Bondi Beach]]. At the same time he conceived and appeared in a controversial television documentary, ''Kids of the [[Kings Cross, New South Wales|Cross]]'', where Luhrmann, embedded as a character, lived with a group of street kids.<ref>{{IMDb title|id=2201089|title=Kids of the Cross}}</ref> In 1983, he began an acting course at the [[National Institute of Dramatic Art]]. He graduated in 1985 alongside [[Sonia Todd]], [[Catherine McClements]] and [[Justin Monjo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nida.edu.au/ALUMNI/default.aspx |title=NIDA Alumni |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014011919/http://www.nida.edu.au/ALUMNI/default.aspx |archivedate=14 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On [[Australia Day|26 January]] 1997, he married [[Catherine Martin (designer)|Catherine Martin]], a [[production designer]]; the couple have two children.\n\nLuhrmann supports the [[Melbourne Football Club|Melbourne Demons]] in the [[Australian Football League]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Beveridge|first1=Riley|title=Your AFL club's most famous supporters, from Barack Obama to Cam Newton|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/your-afl-clubs-most-famous-supporters-from-barack-obama-to-cam-newton/news-story/03eb54659866d587cf9c2cc4b9f3d8c5|website=Fox Sports|accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Films==\n[[File:BazLuhrmann2.png|thumb|Luhrmann in 2018]]\nAfter theatrical successes, including the original stage version of ''Strictly Ballroom'', Luhrmann moved into film and has directed five so far:\n*''[[Strictly Ballroom]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Romeo + Juliet]]'' (1996)\n*''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'' (2001)\n*''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]'' (2008)\n*''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]'' (2013)\n\nThe modern film interpretation ''[[Romeo + Juliet]]'', starring [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] and [[Claire Danes]], defeated ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'' at the BAFTAs for best direction, music and screenplay. The film was celebrated at the Berlin Film Festival, where it was recognised with the Gold Bear award for direction and Silver Bear for DiCaprio's performance. Luhrmann also produced both volumes of the soundtrack album, which went triple-platinum.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chagollan |first1=Steve |title='Gatsby's' Great Music Collection |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/features/gatsby-1200370682/ |website=Variety |publisher=Penske Business Media, LLC |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nLuhrmann's Oscar-winning musical ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'' (2001), set in the Montmartre Quarter of Paris at the dawn of the 20th century, told the story of a young English poet/writer, Christian ([[Ewan McGregor]]) who falls in love with the star of the Moulin Rouge, cabaret actress and courtesan Satine ([[Nicole Kidman]]). The film was praised by its adherents, including famed musical directors [[Robert Wise]] and [[Stanley Donen]], as having re-invented the modern musical, blending decades of popular music in remixes and mash-ups.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Berk |first1=Philip |title=2002 \u2013 Musical or Comedy: ''Moulin Rouge!''|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/articles/2002-musical-or-comedy-moulin-rouge |website=Golden Globe Awards |publisher=HFPA |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> The movie was named one of the AFI's top ten films of 2001<ref>{{cite web |title=American Film Institute's Top Films of the Year|url=http://www.infoplease.com/ipea/A0878236.html|work=InfoPlease|accessdate=28 June 2011}}</ref> and in 2010 was chosen as the top film of the 2000s decade in a poll of 150,000 respondents in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|title=Moulin Rouge! voted best film of the decade|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/film-news/6944981/NEEDS-PIC-Moulin-Rouge-voted-best-film-of-the-decade.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=7 January 2010|accessdate=28 June 2011|location=London}}</ref> At the 59th Annual Golden Globes, Moulin Rouge! took home the awards for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress]], and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Winners & Nominees 2002 |url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2002 |website=Golden Globe Awards |publisher=HFPA |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> The film also gave birth to a successful soundtrack album, produced by Luhrmann, which sold more than seven million copies and went double-platinum, led by the Grammy-winning number one hit single \"[[Lady Marmalade]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Lady Marmalade Wins Grammy Award|url=http://www.bignoisenow.com/christina/grammy02win.html|publisher=BigNoiseNow|date=28 February 2002|accessdate=28 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Chagollan |first1=Steve |title='Gatsby's' Great Music Collection |url=https://variety.com/2013/film/features/gatsby-1200370682/ |website=Variety |publisher=Penske Business Media |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nLuhrmann's 2008 historical epic ''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]'' featured some of the country's most celebrated actors, including [[Nicole Kidman]], [[Hugh Jackman]], and [[David Gulpilil]]. Situated between the two World Wars, the film blended a nostalgic romance with major events from Australian history, including the [[Bombing of Darwin]], and the true story of the [[Stolen Generations]], wherein thousands of mixed-race Aboriginal children were stolen from their families by the state and forcibly integrated into white society. The movie's racial politics were controversial for their time, and notably, its production coincided with Prime Minister Kevin Rudd's 2008 [[Apology to Australia's Indigenous peoples]]. [[Marcia Langton]], professor of Australian indigenous studies at [[University of Melbourne|Melbourne University]] publicly supported the film, saying \"Luhrmann depicts with satirical sharpness the racial caste system of that time... In his imagined cinema of the 1940s, the spatial and social shape of racism is reconstructed with such exact detail, I felt I had been transported back to my own childhood.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Langton |first1=Marcia |title=Faraway Downs fantasy resonates close to home |url=https://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/faraway-downs-fantasy-resonates-close-to-home-20081123-ge7jaa.html |website=The Age |accessdate=7 March 2019}}</ref> While achieving modest box office success in the United States, the film was very successful in Europe, maintaining the #1 slot at the box office for many weeks in France, Germany, Spain, Italy and the Scandinavian countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=australia.htm|website=Box Office Mojo|title=Australia|accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> It is the second-highest grossing Australian film of all time, next to ''[[Crocodile Dundee]]'' and ahead of ''[[Happy Feet]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Highest Grossing Aussie Films|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/1009915/highest-grossing-aussie-films|work=World News Australia|publisher=Published by SBS|date=27 February 2009|accessdate=28 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Luhrmann [[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|adapted]] F. Scott Fitzgerald's ''[[The Great Gatsby]]'', shot in 3D,<ref>{{cite news|title=Baz Luhrmann eyes ''Great Gatsby''|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117997638.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|author=Michael Jones|date=18 December 2008|accessdate=11 August 2009}}</ref> starring [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] as [[Jay Gatsby]], [[Tobey Maguire]] as [[Nick Carraway]], [[Carey Mulligan]] as [[Daisy Buchanan]], [[Joel Edgerton]] as Tom Buchanan, Australian newcomer [[Elizabeth Debicki]] as Jordan Baker, and legendary Indian actor [[Amitabh Bachchan]] as Meyer Wolfsheim. For the film, Luhrmann and costume/production designer Catherine Martin collaborated with [[Prada]], [[Brooks Brothers]], and [[Tiffany & Co]] to create period-inspired dresses, suits, and jewelry based on their own archives and true to the book's own references to luxury brands.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Lucie |title=Luxury brands and 'The Great Gatsby' movie |url=https://www.ft.com/content/c8098b7e-ace8-11e2-b27f-00144feabdc0 |website=Financial Times |publisher=The Financial Times LTD |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> The film grossed over $353 million worldwide, making it the director's highest-grossing movie to date.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Great Gatsby |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=greatgatsby2012.htm |website=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Baz Luhrmann |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Director&id=bazluhrmann.htm |website=Box Office Mojo |publisher=IMDb |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> Critic Richard Roeper described the adaptation as \"the best attempt yet to capture the essence of the novel\u201d while Fitzgerald's granddaughter praised the movie, saying \"Scott would have been proud.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Roeper |first1=Richard |title=The Great Gatsby |url=http://www.richardroeper.com/reviews/thegreatgatsby.aspx |website=RichardRoeper.com |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kendall |first1=Mary Claire |title=\"Loving 'Gatsby' All About 'Living Fitzgerald'\" |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maryclairekendall/2013/05/10/loving-gatsby-all-about-living-fitzgerald/#3dd5537a611f |website=Forbes |publisher=Forbes Media LLC |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> The following year, at the [[86th Academy Awards]], the film won in both of its nominated categories: [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]] and [[Academy Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The 86th Academy Awards \u2013 2014|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2014 |website=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> The soundtrack, produced by Luhrmann, Anton Monsted, and [[Jay-Z]], sought to blend the music of the Jazz Age with contemporary hip-hop as two historical analogues.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Young |first1=Alex |title=The Great Gatsby soundtrack features new Jay-Z, The xx, Florence & the Machine |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2013/04/the-great-gatsby-soundtrack-features-new-jay-z-the-xx-florence-the-machine/ |website=Consequence of Sound |publisher=Consequence of Sound |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> Featured artists included [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Jack White]], [[Lana Del Rey]], [[Sia (musician)|Sia]], [[will.i.am]], [[The xx]], and [[Florence and the Machine]]; the soundtrack also included score from the film's composer and Luhrmann's repeat collaborator [[Craig Armstrong (composer)|Craig Armstrong]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blistein |first1=Jon |title='Great Gatsby' Soundtrack Featured Jay-Z, Andre 3000, Beyonce |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/great-gatsby-soundtrack-features-jay-z-andre-3000-beyonce-186765/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref> The album's sales exceeded expectations, marking the biggest digital sales week for a soundtrack in Billboard history, and peaking at number one on the US Billboard 200 chart.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Corner |first1=Lewis |title='Great Gatsby', Lady Antebellum storm US album chart |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/music/a481948/great-gatsby-lady-antebellum-storm-us-album-chart/ |website=Digital Spy |publisher=National Magazine Company, Ltd. |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Soundtrack Chart History |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/soundtrack/chart-history/alternative-albums |website=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media, LLC |accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nLuhrmann is currently in pre-production for a film about [[Elvis Presley]]'s relationship with [[Colonel Tom Parker]], set to start filming in February 2020 and due to be released in October 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/dune-baz-luhrmann-elvis-presley-movie-release-dates-1202660346/|title=Warner Bros. Dates Baz Luhrmann \u2018Elvis Presley\u2019 Movie, Shifts \u2018Dune\u2019 & More|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-08-02|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref> In March 2018, it was announced that [[Tom Hanks]] would play Parker and later in July, news broke that [[Austin Butler]] had been cast as the famed singer after a series of screen tests, as well as music and performance workshops.<ref>https://deadline.com/2019/07/elvis-presley-movie-baz-luhrmann-ansel-elgort-miles-teller-austin-butler-harry-styles-tom-hanks-1202640766/</ref><ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/harry-styles-ansel-elgort-miles-teller-running-play-elvis-baz-luhrmann-film-1222173</ref><ref>https://news.avclub.com/baz-luhrmanns-elvis-biopic-finds-its-star-austin-butle-1836382932</ref>\n\n==Television==\n[[File:Baz Luhrmann Cannes 2013.jpg|thumb|upright|Luhrmann at the [[2013 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\nIn 2016, Luhrmann collaborated with award-winning playwright [[Stephen Adly Guirgis]] on the [[Netflix]] series ''[[The Get Down]]'' about the birth of [[hip-hop]] in the 1970s.<ref>Hetrick, Adam. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/baz-luhrmann-and-stephen-adly-guirgis-collaborating-on-hip-hop-television-p-212833 \"Baz Luhrmann and Stephen Adly Guirgis Collaborating on Hip-Hop Television Project\"]. ''[[Playbill]]'', December 13, 2013</ref> For the series, Luhrmann brought on [[Nas]], [[Grandmaster Flash]], [[Kurtis Blow]] and [[DJ Kool Herc]] as producers, to help tell the story of the rise of hip hop, punk, and disco during shifting cultural and political transformation through his unique brand of magical realism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/1263-netflixs-the-get-down-is-the-rare-and-great-music-drama-thats-actually-about-music/|title=Netflix\u2019s \"The Get Down\" Is the Rare (And Great) Music Drama That\u2019s Actually About Music|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> The series featured two parts, praised for its vibrant music, fresh cast and authenticity, due to the involvement of many of the era's key historical figures in central roles to the show's development.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Get Down|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_get_down|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> Part One was certified fresh by [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with a score of 77%, while Part Two of the series holds a critic score of 86%.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Get Down: Season One |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_get_down/s01 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Get Down: Season Two |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_get_down/s02 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Acting and director credits==\n\n===Director credits===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Film\n! Year\n! Awards\n|-\n| ''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n|1992\n| [[Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts|AFI Award]] for Best Director<br/>AFI Award for Best Screenplay<br/>[[London Critics Circle Film Awards|ALFS Award]] for Newcomer of the Year<br/>Nominated\u2014[[BAFTA Film Award]] for Best Adapted Screenplay<br/>Nominated\u201420/20 Award for Best Original Screenplay\n|-\n|''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''\n|1996\n| [[51st British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Award]] for [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]<br/>BAFTA Award for [[BAFTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[Berlin International Film Festival|Golden Bear Award]] for Best Picture\n|-\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|2001\n| [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]<br/>[[National Board of Review|National Board of Review Award]] for [[National Board of Review Award for Best Film|Best Film]]<br/>[[Producers Guild of America Award]] for Best Picture<br/>[[Satellite Award]] for [[Satellite Award for Best Director|Best Director]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[AACTA Award]] for [[AACTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]<br/>Nominated\u2014AACTA Award for [[AACTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Award]] for [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]<br/>Nominated\u2014BAFTA Award for [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]<br/>Nominated\u2014BAFTA Award for [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]<br/>Nominated\u2014Golden Globe for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director|Best Director]]<br/>Nominated\u2014Satellite Award for [[Satellite Award for Best Film|Best Film]]<br/>Nominated\u2014Satellite Award for [[Satellite Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]\n|-\n|''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]''\n|2008\n| Nominated\u2014[[Satellite Award]] for [[Satellite Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[AACTA Awards|AFI]] [[AFI Members' Choice Award|Members' Choice Award]]\n|-\n|''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]''\n|2013\n| [[AACTA Awards|AACTA Award]] for [[AACTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]<br/>AACTA Award for [[AACTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]<br/>AACTA Award for [[AACTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[AACTA Awards|AACTA International Award]] for [[AACTA International Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media]]<br/>Nominated\u2014[[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association|Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Award]] for [[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n|-\n| ''[[Elvis (2021 film)|Elvis]]''\n|2021\n|\n|}\n\n===Creator===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Film\n! Year\n! Notes\n|-\n|''[[The Get Down]]''\n|2016\u20132017\n|Streaming on [[Netflix]]\n|}\n\n===Screen actor===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Film\n! Year\n! Character\n! Notes\n|-\n| ''[[A Country Practice]]'' (TV) || 1981\u201382 || Jerry Percival || Guest star for six episodes.\n|-\n| ''[[Winter of Our Dreams]]'' (film) || 1981 || Pete || Also starred [[Judy Davis]] and [[Bryan Brown]].\n|-\n| ''[[The Dark Room (1982 film)|The Bedroom]]'' (film) || 1982 || First student || Small role.\n|-\n| ''[[The Highest Honor]]'' (film) || 1982 || Able Seaman A. W. Huston || Also starred [[Steve Bisley]].\n|-\n| ''Kids of the Cross'' (TV documentary) || 1983 || Himself || Filmed in Sydney in 1981. Produced by [[Mike Willesee]].\n|}\n\n===Stage actor===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Name\n! Year\n! Character\n! Notes\n|-\n| ''Are You Lonesome Tonight?'' || 1982 || Unknown || Performed at Nimrod Downstairs, Sydney. Directed by Peter Kingston.\n|-\n| ''Fanshen'' || 1983 || Peasant || Performed at [[National Institute of Dramatic Art|NIDA]], Sydney.\n|-\n| ''[[Summerfolk|Holiday Makers]]'' || 1984 || Unknown || Performed at NIDA. Directed by [[Nick Enright]].\n|-\n| ''[[All's Well That Ends Well]]'' || 1984 || Dumain Brother || Performed at NIDA. Directed by Kevin Jackson.\n|-\n| ''[[Strictly Ballroom]]'' || 1984; 1986 || Ross Pierce || Performed at NIDA in 1984, and in [[Bratislava]] in 1986; also directed.\n|-\n| ''[[A Dream Play|Dreamplay]]'' || 1985 || Unknown || Performed at NIDA. Directed by [[Jim Sharman]].\n|-\n| ''[[Funeral Games (play)|Funeral Games]]'' || 1985 || Unknown || Part of the ''Hallucinogenics? 3 plays from the 60s'' event. Performed at NIDA. Directed by Egil Kipste.\n|-\n| ''[[Chamber Music (play)|Chamber Music]]'' || 1985 || Unknown || Part of the ''Hallucinogenics? 3 plays from the 60s'' event. Performed at NIDA. Directed by Ros Horin.\n|-\n| ''The Greeks'' || 1985 || Unknown || Trilogy: ''The War'', ''The Murders'', ''The Gods''. Performed at NIDA, and St Martin's Youth Arts Centre, [[Melbourne]].\n|-\n| ''[[Once in a Lifetime (play)|Once in a Lifetime]]'' || 1985 || Unknown || Performed at NIDA. Directed by [[Gale Edwards]].\n|-\n| ''Crocodile Creek'' || 1986 || \u2013 || Directed for the New Moon Theatre Company in [[Rockhampton]]. Amateur musical production set in the Queensland goldfields.\n|-\n| ''The Conquest of the South Pole'' || 1989 || Unknown || Performed at [[Belvoir St Theatre]], Sydney. Directed by [[Jim Sharman]].\n|}\n\n==Other work==\n{{prose|section|date=October 2019}}\n*'''1981:''' A young Luhrmann can be seen in an early acting role in the film ''[[Winter of Our Dreams]]'', directed by [[John Duigan]]. Luhrmann has a small part playing opposite [[Judy Davis]].\n*'''1992:''' Luhrmann directed a video for [[John Paul Young]]'s \"Love Is in the Air\", which was rereleased to coincide with the release of ''Strictly Ballroom'' in which the song was featured prominently.\n*'''1993:''' Luhrmann staged his interpretation of [[Benjamin Britten]]'s version of ''[[A Midsummer Night's Dream (opera)|A Midsummer Night's Dream]]'', set in colonial India, for the [[Australian Opera]]. After successful seasons in Sydney and Melbourne, the production went on to win the Critics' Prize at the [[Edinburgh Festival]]. Music extracts can be heard on his album ''[[Something for Everybody (Baz Luhrmann album)|Something for Everybody]]''.\n*'''1993:''' Luhrmann assisted in the election campaign of former Australian prime minister [[Paul Keating]].\n*'''1997:''' The CD of ''Something for Everybody'' was released, featuring music from Luhrmann's films and operas including his version of Britten's ''A Midsummer Night's Dream''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/release/1255770|title=Bazmark Inc. Presents Something For Everybody (CD, Comp)|work=Discogs}}</ref> Moreover, Luhrmann created his own company with his wife [[Catherine Martin (designer)|Catherine Martin]]: {{ill|Bazmark|fr}}.\n*'''1999:''' As a music producer, Luhrmann is credited with \"[[Everybody's Free (To Wear Sunscreen)]]\", a successful [[spoken word]] song in Europe and the Americas.\n*'''2002:''' Luhrmann brought his production of [[Giacomo Puccini|Puccini]]'s ''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' to the [[Broadway Theatre (53rd Street)|Broadway Theatre]] in New York City. Originally produced for [[Opera Australia]] in Sydney in 1990, once in New York it eventually received seven [[Tony Award]] nominations, including Best Revival of a Musical, Best Direction (Luhrmann), Best Orchestrations (Nicholas Kitsopoulos), Best Costume Design (Catherine Martin), and winning Best Set Design (Catherine Martin), Best Lighting Design (Nigel Levings), and the [[Tony Honors for Excellence in Theatre]] for the Principal Ensemble Cast.\n*'''2004:''' Luhrmann directed a lavish multimillion-dollar commercial for [[Chanel N\u00b0 5]] titled ''[[No. 5 the Film|N\u00b0 5 the Film]]'', inspired by his Red Curtain trilogy, starring Nicole Kidman and [[Rodrigo Santoro]]. On the ''[[Charlie Rose (TV series)|Charlie Rose]]'' interview show he told Rose that he based the commercial on the 1953 film ''[[Roman Holiday]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlierose.com/view/interview/9669 |title=Charlie Rose \u2013 A conversation about the film \"Australia\" |author=Luhrmann, Baz |work=[[The Charlie Rose Show]] |date=27 November 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402111603/http://www.charlierose.com/view/interview/9669 |archivedate=2 April 2015 }}</ref>\n*'''2005:''' Luhrmann was appointed an Ambassador for the [[Australian Theatre for Young People]].\n*'''2008:''' Luhrmann was asked by the Prime Minister of Australia [[Kevin Rudd]] to make new advertisements to promote Australia as a tourist destination.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601081&sid=aqTdor3btTDI|title=Australia Taps Luhrmann for Campaign to Boost Tourism|first=Malcolm|last=Scott|publisher=Bloomberg.com|date=29 July 2008}}</ref>\n*'''2009:''' At the [[81st Academy Awards]] in February, Luhrmann put together a number dedicated to musicals which consisted of [[Hugh Jackman]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Zac Efron]], [[Vanessa Hudgens]], [[Dominic Cooper]] and [[Amanda Seyfried]].\n*'''2009:''' In September, Luhrmann made an appearance as a guest judge on ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 9)|Dancing with the Stars]]''.\n*'''2010:''' Luhrmann and the painter Vincent Fantauzzo embarked on an art initiative which took them to India, where they created artworks on walls of hotels, in the streets of Rajasthan and on 17th century forts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnngo.com/mumbai/play/baz-luhrmann-vincent-fantauzzos-mad-indian-motorcycle-diary-016354|title=Baz Luhrmann & Vincent Fantauzzo's mad Indian motorcycle diary|author=Kanwardeep Singh Dhaliwal|publisher=CNNgo.com|date=24 March 2010|access-date=27 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114134252/http://www.cnngo.com/mumbai/play/baz-luhrmann-vincent-fantauzzos-mad-indian-motorcycle-diary-016354|archive-date=14 January 2012|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n*'''2017:''' Luhrmann shot the campaign film ''The Secret Life of Flowers'' for the collaboration between [[Erdem Moral\u0131o\u011flu|Erdem]] and [[H&M]].<ref>{{YouTube|PEANC3ipyws|ERDEM x H&M \u2013 ''The Secret Life of Flowers'' campaign film by Baz Luhrmann}}</ref>\n*'''2019:''' Though mostly hands-off with the stage production of [[Moulin Rouge! (musical)|''Moulin Rouge!'' (musical)]], Luhrmann produced its Broadway cast recording.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/09/02/baz-luhrmanns-moulin-rouge-mega-mashup|title=Baz Luhrmann\u2019s \"Moulin Rouge!\" Mega Mashup|last=Schulman|first=Michael|date=2019-08-26|access-date=2019-10-22|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n\n==Collaborations==\nLuhrmann has cast certain actors in more than one of his films:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!\n! ''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n! ''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''\n! ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n! ''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]''\n!''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]''\n|-\n|Veronica Beattie\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Max Cullen]]\n|\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Leonardo DiCaprio]]\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Arthur Dignam]]\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|Steven Grace\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Nigel Harbach\n|\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|Michelle Hopper\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Bill Hunter (actor)|Bill Hunter]]\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|-\n|[[Nicole Kidman]]\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|-\n|[[Jacek Koman]]\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[John Leguizamo]]\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Tara Morice]]\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Lara Mulcahy\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Barry Otto]]\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|John Sheerin\n|\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Jack Thompson (actor)|Jack Thompson]]\n|\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|-\n|[[Kerry Walker]]\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|-\n|[[David Wenham]]\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|-\n|[[Peter Whitford]]\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|\n|\n|-\n|Matthew Whittet\n|\n|\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|<center>{{X mark}}</center>\n|}\n\n==Influences==\nLuhrmann has cited [[Grand opera#Italy|Italian grand opera]] as a major influence on his work and has also given a nod to other theatrical styles, such as [[Bollywood]] films, as having influenced his style. Luhrmann was a ballroom dancer as a child and his mother taught ballroom dancing which was an inspiration for ''Strictly Ballroom''. Luhrmann's favourite films are ''[[Star 80]]'', ''[[8\u00bd]]'', ''[[War and Peace (film series)|War and Peace]]'', ''[[Medium Cool]]'' and ''[[Fitzcarraldo]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/william_shakespeares_romeo_and_juliet/news/1921010/five_favorite_films_with_baz_luhrmann|title=Five Favorite Films of Baz Luhrmann}} Rotten Tomatoes. 19 October 2010. Retrieved 29 March 2013.</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n\n=== AACTA Awards ===\nLuhrmann has received four awards from nine  [[AACTA Awards|Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts Awards]] nominations.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n|Best Director\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":0\">{{IMDb title|id=0105488|title=Strictly Ballroom|section=awards}}</ref>\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n|Best Screenplay, Original or Adapted\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''\n|Best Foreign Film\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":1\">{{IMDb title|id=0117509|title=Romeo + Juliet|section=awards}}</ref>\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Direction\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\">{{IMDb title|id=0203009|title=Moulin Rouge!|section=awards}}</ref>\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Film\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]''\n|Best Original Score\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":3\">{{IMDb title|id=0455824|title=Australia|section=awards}}</ref>\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]''\n|News Limited Readers' Choice Award\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|[[3rd AACTA Awards|2014]]\n|''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]''\n|Best Direction\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":4\">{{IMDb title|id=1343092|title=The Great Gatsby|section=awards}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[3rd AACTA Awards|2014]]\n|''[[The Great Gatsby (2013 film)|The Great Gatsby]]''\n|Best Film\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":4\" />\n|}\n\n=== Academy Awards ===\n''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'' was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] at the [[74th Academy Awards]]. Luhrmann was not nominated for Best Director, prompting host [[Whoopi Goldberg]] to remark, \"I guess [it] just directed itself.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/oscar-insanity-132261|title=Oscar Insanity|date=2003-03-11|work=Newsweek|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|[[74th Academy Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Picture\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|}\n\n=== British Academy Film Awards ===\nLuhrmann has received two awards from seven [[British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Award]] nominations.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|[[46th British Academy Film Awards|1993]]\n|''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n|Best Screenplay, Adapted\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[46th British Academy Film Awards|1993]]\n|''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n|Best Film\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[51st British Academy Film Awards|1998]]\n|''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''\n|Best Screenplay, Adapted\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[51st British Academy Film Awards|1998]]\n|''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''\n|David Lean Award for Direction\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[55th British Academy Film Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Screenplay\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|[[55th British Academy Film Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|David Lean Award for Direction\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|[[55th British Academy Film Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Film\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|}\n\n=== Golden Globe Awards ===\nLuhrmann has been nominated three times for [[Golden Globe Award]]s, winning in 2002 for Best Motion Picture, Comedy or Musical\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|[[51st Golden Globe Awards|1994]]\n|''[[Strictly Ballroom]]''\n|Best Motion Picture, Comedy or Musical\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[59th Golden Globe Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Motion Picture, Comedy or Musical\n|{{won}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|[[59th Golden Globe Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n|Best Director, Motion Picture\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|}\n\n=== Grammy Awards ===\nLuhrmann has been specifically been nominated three times for [[Grammy Award]]s, with additional accolades for songs on the albums he has produced for his films, including wins for [[Lady Marmalade]] at [[44th Annual Grammy Awards|2002's Grammy's]] ([[Grammy Award for Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals]]), as well as nominations for [[Young and Beautiful (Lana Del Rey song)]] for the [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media]] the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards|2014 Grammy's]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|[[44th Annual Grammy Awards|2002]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge! Music from Baz Luhrmann's Film]]''\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|[[56th Annual Grammy Awards|2014]]\n|''[[The Great Gatsby: Music from Baz Luhrmann's Film]]''\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media|Best Compilation Soundtrack for Visual Media]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|-\n|[[62nd Annual Grammy Awards|2020]]\n|''[[Moulin Rouge! (musical)|Moulin Rouge! The Musical]]'' Original Broadway Cast Recording\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album|Best Musical Theater Album]]\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|}\n\n=== Tony Awards ===\nLuhrmann has specifically been nominated for two [[Tony Award]]s, and his production of ''[[La boh\u00e8me#Modernizations|La Boheme]]'' also won awards for Best Scenic Design and Best Lighting Design at the [[57th Tony Awards]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|2003\n|[[La boh\u00e8me#Modernizations|''La boh\u00e8me'']]\n|Best Direction in a Musical\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":5\">{{IBDB title|id=13346#awards|title=La Boh\u00e8me}}</ref>\n|-\n|2003\n|[[La boh\u00e8me#Modernizations|''La boh\u00e8me'']]\n|Best Revival of a Musical\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":5\" />\n|}\n\n=== Additional awards ===\n*[[American Film Institute#AFI Awards|AFI Awards]], USA \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, AFI Film Award; AFI Movie of the Year for ''Moulin Rouge''\n*[[Australians in Film]] \u2013\n**2013 \u2013 Won, Orry-Kelly International Award Honoree\n*[[47th Berlin International Film Festival|Berlin International Film Festival]] \u2013 1997 \u2013 Won, [[Alfred Bauer Prize]] for ''William Shakespeare's Romeo + Juliet''; Nominated, Golden Berlin Bear for ''William Shakespeare's Romeo + Juliet''<ref name=\"Berlinale 1997\">{{cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1997/03_preistr_ger_1997/03_Preistraeger_1997.html|title=Berlinale: 1997 Prize Winners|accessdate=12 January 2012|work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n*[[Bodil Awards]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, Bodil, Best Non-American Film (Bedste ikke amerikanske film) for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*Bogota Film Festival \u2013 1994 \u2013 Nominated, Golden Precolumbian Circle. Best Film for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*[[Broadcast Film Critics Association Awards]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Won, Critics Choice Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Cannes Film Festival]] \u2013\n**2001 \u2013 Nominated, Palme d'Or for ''Moulin Rouge!'';\n**1992 \u2013 Won, Award of the Youth, Foreign Film for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*[[Chicago Film Critics Association Awards]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, CFCA Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Clio Awards]] \u2013  2016 \u2013  Won, Honorary Award<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://clios.com/news/2016-honorary-award-recipient-baz-luhrmann|title=2016 Honorary Award Recipient: Baz Luhrmann|date=2016-09-26|work=Clios|access-date=2018-01-31|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*[[C\u00e9sar Awards]], France \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, C\u00e9sar, Best Foreign Film (Meilleur film \u00e9tranger) for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Drama Desk Award]]  \u2013  2003  \u2013  Nominated, Outstanding Revival of a Musical and Best Direction for [[La boh\u00e8me#Modernizations|''La Boheme'']]<ref name=\":5\" />\n*[[Directors Guild of America]], USA \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, DGA Award, Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Motion Pictures for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Empire Awards]], UK \u2013 2002 \u2013 Won, Empire Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[European Film Awards]] \u2013\n**2001 \u2013 Won, Screen International Award for ''Moulin Rouge!'';\n**1997 \u2013 Nominated, Screen International Award for ''William Shakespeare's Romeo + Juliet''\n*[[Film Critics Circle of Australia Awards]] \u2013\n**2009 \u2013 Nominated, FCCA Award, Best Film for ''[[Australia (2008 film)|Australia]]'';\n**2002 \u2013 Won, FCCA Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''; Nominated, FCCA Award, Best Screenplay \u2013 Original for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Hollywood Film Festival]] \u2013 2001 \u2013 Won, Hollywood Movie of the Year for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Inside Film Awards]] \u2013 2001 \u2013 Nominated, Best Feature Film for ''Moulin Rouge!''; Nominated, Best Direction for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Italian National Syndicate of Film Journalists]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, Silver Ribbon, Best Director \u2013 Foreign Film (Regista del Miglior Film Straniero) for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[London Critics Circle Film Awards]] \u2013\n**1998 \u2013 Nominated, ALFS Award, Director of the Year for ''William Shakespeare's Romeo + Juliet'';\n**1993 \u2013 Won, ALFS Award, Newcomer of the Year for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*Love is Folly International Film Festival, Bulgaria \u2013 1993 \u2013 Won, Golden Aphrodite for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*[[MTV Movie & TV Awards]] \u2013 1997 \u2013 Nominated, Best Movie for [[Romeo + Juliet]]\n*[[Online Film Critics Society Awards]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, OFCS Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Producers Guild of America Award]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Won, Motion Picture Producer of the Year Award for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Palm Springs International Film Festival]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Won, Sonny Bono Visionary Award\n*Phoenix Film Critics Society Awards \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, PFCS Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*Robert Festival \u2013\n**2002 \u2013 Won, Robert, Best Non-American Film (\u00c5rets ikke-amerikanske film) for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n**1993 \u2013 Won, Robert, Best Foreign Film (\u00c5rets udenlandske spillefilm) for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*[[Satellite Awards]] \u2013\n**2008 \u2013 Won, Auteur Award, Nominated, Satellite Award, Best Screenplay, Original for ''Australia''; Nominated, Satellite Award, Best Original Song for ''Australia'' for the song \"By the Boab Tree\";\n**2002 \u2013 Won, Golden Satellite Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''. Nominated, Golden Satellite Award, Best Screenplay, Original for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Teen Choice Awards]] \u2013 \n**2002 \u2013 Nominated, Film \u2013 Choice Movie, Drama/Action/Adventure for ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]''\n**2009 \u2013 Nominated, Film \u2013 Choice Movie, Romance for ''[[Australia (2008 film)]]''\n*[[Toronto International Film Festival]] \u2013 1992 \u2013 Won, People's Choice Award for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*[[Vancouver Film Critics Circle]] \u2013 2002 \u2013 Won, VFCC Award, Best Director for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Vancouver International Film Festival]] \u2013 1992 \u2013 Won, Most Popular Film for ''Strictly Ballroom''\n*World Soundtrack Awards \u2013 2001 \u2013 Won, World Soundtrack Award, Most Creative Use of Existing Material on a Soundtrack for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n*[[Writers Guild of America Award]], USA \u2013 2002 \u2013 Nominated, WGA Award (Screen), Best Screenplay Written Directly for the Screen for ''Moulin Rouge!''\n\n== Media appearances ==\n*In September 2009, Luhrmann made an appearance as a guest judge on ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 9)|Dancing with the Stars]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Baz Luhrmann Guest Judges On ''Dancing''|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/09/28/baz-luhrmann-guest-judges_n_302461.html|accessdate=6 February 2014|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=28 September 2009}}</ref> Luhrmann participated on the [[NPR]] radio quiz program ''[[Wait Wait... Don't Tell Me!]]'' in 2013.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2013/09/07/219704753/not-my-job-we-ask-australian-baz-luhrmann-about-austria ''Wait Wait...Don't Tell Me!''] from [[National Public Radio|NPR]]</ref>\n*Luhrmann's No1 song hit from 1999,  \"Everybody's Free (To Wear Sunscreen)\" from the album [[Something for Everybody (Baz Luhrmann album)]] also known as \"The Sunscreen Song\" was discussed (04/03/2020) on the [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] [[Adrian Chiles]] Chiles on Friday programme with Charlotte McDonald. Whose original full length documentary can be listened to on the [[BBC World Service]]''The Documentary, The Sunscreen Song; The Class of '99''<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w3cszvtr|Documentary, The Sunscreen Song; The Class of '99]</ref> It featured an interview from the documentary with Australian voice over artist, [[Lee Perry (voice actor)|Lee Perry]]\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Baz Luhrmann}}\n* {{official website|http://www.bazmark.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|525303}}\n\n{{Baz Luhrmann}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Baz Luhrmann\n| list =\n{{AACTA Award Best Direction}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Direction 1985\u20132009}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay 1983\u20131999}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Director}}\n{{Empire Award for Best Director}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Director}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luhrmann, Baz}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:ARIA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Australian film directors]]\n[[Category:Australian opera directors]]\n[[Category:Australian film producers]]\n[[Category:Australian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Australian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Best Director BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Director Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:European Film Awards winners (people)]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:National Institute of Dramatic Art alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Sydney]]\n", "name_user": "Michael Bednarek", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix URL for Chiles & trim.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baz_Luhrmann"}
{"title_page": "Ma Yashu", "text_new": "{{short description|Chinese actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ma Yashu\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name  = \n| other_names = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1977|03|24}} \n| birth_place = [[Kunming]], [[Yunnan]], China\n| death_date  = <!-- {{death date and age|}} -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| alma_mater  = [[National Academy of Chinese Theatre Arts]]\n| occupation  = Actress\n| years_active= 1995&ndash;present\n| organization= \n| agent       = \n| known_for   = \n| notable_works = \n| television  = \n| party       = \n| movement    = \n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Nicky Wu]]|2006|2009}}{{marriage|James Robert Hayes|2010}}\n| partner     = \n| children    = Mia Hayes (daughter) <br> Aiden Hayes (son)\n| parents            = <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n| mother             = <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| father             = <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| relatives          = Atina Robert (stepdaughter)\n| family             = \n| callsign           = \n| website            = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| awards      = <!--  {{Awards|award= |year= |title= }} -->\n| signature   = \n| signature_size = \n| module  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n|s = {{linktext|\u9a6c|\u96c5|\u8212}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u99ac|\u96c5|\u8212}}\n|p = M\u01ce Y\u01cesh\u016b \n|s2 = {{linktext|\u9a6c|\u5a05|\u8212}}\n|t2 = {{linktext|\u99ac|\u5a6d|\u8212}}\n|p2 =  M\u01ce Y\u01cesh\u016b \n|w = \n}}\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Ma (surname)|Ma]]}} \n'''Ma Yashu''' ({{zh|s=\u9a6c\u96c5\u8212|t=|p=}}; born 24 March 1977) is a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] actress best known for her roles as Bai Lianhua and He Xiaoxi in the television series ''Journey to the West'' (2000) and ''The Story of Parents House'' (2008) respectively.\n\n==Early life and education==\nMa was born in [[Kunming]], [[Yunnan]] on March 24, 1977. In 1986 she was accepted to the [[National Academy of Chinese Theatre Arts]].\n\n==Acting career==\nMa made her film debut in ''Beijing Girl'' (1989), playing Jin Jing.\n\nIn 1995, Ma made her television debut in ''Legendary Life''.\n\nIn 1996, she had a minor role as Bi Zhu in ''The Greatness of a Hero'', which starred Sun Chengzheng as [[Di Renjie]]. That same year, she had a cameo appearance in the historical television series ''Heroes in Sui and Tang Dynasties'', a television series adaptation based on the novel of the same name.\n\nMa starred in a television series called ''Journey to the West'' with Cao Rong, Huang Haibing, and Wu Jian. It is a sequel to ''[[Journey to the West (1986 TV series)|Journey to the West]]''.\n\nIn 2002 she co-starred with [[Nicky Wu]] and [[Athena Chu]] in the [[wuxia]] television series ''Treasure Raiders'', adapted from Taiwanese novelist [[Gu Long]]'s novel of the same title.\n\nMa had a supporting role in ''Fate in Tears and Laughter'' (2004), based on the novel by the same name by [[Zhang Henshui]]. She played a supporting role in ''Heroes on a Silk Road'', starring Nicky Wu and [[Theresa Lee]] and directed by [[Chin Siu-ho]].\n\nIn 2005, she appeared in ''[[The Legend of Hero]]'', a Taiwanese television series adapted from the Hong Kong [[manhua]] series ''[[Chinese Hero: Tales of the Blood Sword]]'' by [[Ma Wing-shing]]. It was produced by [[Young Pei-pei]] and starred [[Peter Ho]] and [[An Yixuan|Ady An]] in the leading roles. She starred with Nicky Wu, Chin Siu-ho and [[Alex To]] in ''Iron Fisted Drifter''. She also appeared in ''Girls' Dairy'', opposite [[Yang Zi (actress)|Yang Zi]].\n\nMa was cast as Zhao Yuhua in ''Prince to Pauper'' (2007), opposite [[Du Chun]] and [[Hawick Lau]].\n\nIn 2008, she played the female lead role in ''Medic'', alongside [[Deng Chao]] and [[Li Xiaoran]]. She starred as Chun Tao, reuniting her with co-star [[Jia Nailiang]], who played her lover, in the TV drama ''Chun Tao's War''.<ref>{{cite news|editor1=Bu Lu ({{lang|zh|\u5e03\u9c81}})|url=http://yule.sohu.com/20100914/n274928617.shtml |script-title=zh:\u9a6c\u96c5\u8212\u300a\u6625\u6843\u7684\u6218\u4e89\u300b\u6311\u5927\u6881 \u6b32\u8df3\u51fa\u5e74\u4ee3\u620f\u602a\u5708 |work=Sohu |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=zh}}</ref> She appeared in ''The Story of Parents House''. She continued in the role in the 2011 television series ''The Story of Parents House 3'', and 2016's ''The Story of Parents House 4''.\n\nMa played Liu Qizhen, the lead role in He Liping's romantic television series ''Who Knows the Female of the Women'' (2010), costarring Hawick Lau. She co-starred with [[Chen Sicheng]] in ''Pretty Maid''.<ref>{{cite news|editor1=|url=https://ent.qq.com/a/20100520/000161.htm |script-title=zh:\u300a\u5927\u4e2b\u9b1f\u300b\u5c06\u5f00\u64ad \u9a6c\u96c5\u8212\u5927\u79c0\u8ba2\u5a5a\u6212\u201c\u9e3d\u5b50\u86cb\u201d |work=qq.com |date=20 May 2010 |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Ma had a lead role in the TV drama, ''Lock Dream''.<ref>{{cite news|editor1=Wang Xiaoyi ({{lang|zh|\u738b\u6653\u6613}})|url=http://ent.163.com/13/0107/10/8KK22LTS00031GVS.html |script-title=zh:\u300a\u9501\u68a6\u697c\u300b\u591a\u5730\u70ed\u64ad \u9a6c\u96c5\u8212\u9886\u8854\u201c\u5e74\u4ee3\u98ce\u201d |work=163.com |date=7 January 2013 |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nMa took the lead role in the 2018 romantic comedy television series ''Nice to Meet You'', alongside [[Zhang Ming'en]], Wen Yongshan, Wei Qianxiang and Tang Mengjia.<ref>{{cite news|editor1=Xu Shaona ({{lang|zh|\u5f90\u7ecd\u5a1c}})|url=http://ent.people.com.cn/n1/2019/0318/c1012-30980813.html |script-title=zh:\u300a\u53ea\u4e3a\u9047\u89c1\u4f60\u300b\u9a6c\u96c5\u8212\u53d8\u8eab\u5f3a\u52bf\u603b\u88c1\uff1a\u90a3\u4e2a\u6c14\u573a\u597d\u9738\u6c14 |work=people.com.cn |date=18 March 2019 |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, it was reported that Ma was in talks to appear in the television series adaption of [[Jin Yong]]'s wuxia novel ''[[Demi-Gods and Semi-Devils]]'' which will be directed by [[Yu Rongguang]].<ref>{{cite news|editor1=Guo Zehua ({{lang|zh|\u90ed\u6cfd\u534e}})|url=http://www.chinanews.com/yl/2019/01-11/8726470.shtml |script-title=zh:\u300a\u5929\u9f99\u516b\u90e8\u300b\u9996\u53d1\u5267\u7167\u6768\u7950\u5b81\u548c\u6587\u548f\u73ca\u6f14\u7ece\u201c\u5fc3\u201d\u7248\u6c5f\u6e56 |work=Chinanews |date=11 January 2019 |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMa was married to [[Nicky Wu]] in December 2006. They first met while appearing in a Chinese television series ''Treasure Raiders'' in 2001. They divorced on August 11, 2009.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Heidi Hsia |title=Ma Yashu gives blessing to ex-husband, Nicky Wu |url=https://sg.news.yahoo.com/ma-yashu-gives-blessing-ex-husband-nicky-wu-091600814.html |accessdate=14 November 2019 |work=Yahoo |date=18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nicky Wu Had to Clear Legal Issues with Ex-wife Before Marrying Cecilia Liu |url=https://www.jaynestars.com/news/nicky-wu-had-to-clear-legal-issues-with-ex-wife-before-marrying-cecilia-liu/ |accessdate=14 November 2019 |work=jaynestars |date=22 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nicky Wu confirms divorce with actress wife |url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/life/2009-10/22/content_9029425.htm |accessdate=14 November 2019 |work=Chinadaily |date=22 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|editor1=|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/s/h/2009-10-22/09242740360.shtml |script-title=zh:\u72ec\u5bb6\uff1a\u5434\u5947\u9686\u53d1\u58f0\u660e\u627f\u8ba4\u5df2\u79bb\u5a5a |work=sina |date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\nAfter a turbulent divorce, she remarried on June 27, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|editor1=Chen Zhu|url=https://ent.qq.com/a/20100627/000202.htm |script-title=zh:\u9a6c\u96c5\u821227\u65e5\u4e0e\u8001\u5916\u518d\u7ed3\u5a5a \u5a5a\u793c\u73b0\u573a\u70ed\u543b\u7537\u65b9\u6d41\u6cea |work=qq.com |date=27 June 2010 |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=zh}}</ref> Her husband named James Robert Hayes ({{zh|s=\u8a79\u59c6\u65af\u00b7\u7f57\u4f2f\u7279|labels=no}}). The couple has a daughter named Mia ({{zh|s=\u7c73\u96c5|labels=no}}) and a son named Aiden ({{zh|s=\u7231\u767b|labels=no}}).<ref>{{cite news|editor1=Yang Xiaomi ({{lang|zh|\u7f8a\u5c0f\u7c73}})|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/s/m/2013-11-30/07174052482.shtml |script-title=zh:\u53f0\u5a92\u66dd\u9a6c\u96c5\u8212\u63d0\u524d\u5256\u8179 \u4ea76\u65a4\u6df7\u8840\u5973\u5b9d\u5b9d |work=sina |date=30 November 2013 |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=zh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|editor1=|url=http://dy.163.com/v2/article/detail/E8FEDSGR05431BOA.html |script-title=zh:\u9a6c\u96c5\u8212\u4e00\u53cc\u513f\u5973\u8fd1\u7167\u66dd\u5149\uff0c\u5973\u513f\u6f02\u4eae\u513f\u5b50\u5e05\u6c14\uff0c\u4e00\u5bb6\u90fd\u662f\u9ad8\u989c\u503c\uff01 |work=163.com |date=20 February 2019 |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=zh}}</ref> She has a stepdaughter named Atina Robert ({{zh|s=\u963f\u8482\u5a1c\u00b7\u7f57\u4f2f\u7279|labels=no}}).<ref>{{cite news|editor1=|url=https://news.china.com/news100/11038989/20170605/30645695_3.html |script-title=zh:\u9a6c\u96c5\u8212\u5e26\u6df7\u8840\u513f\u5973\u4e0a\u8282\u76ee\uff0c\u6d0b\u8001\u516c\u5f3a\u70c8\u6297\u8bae\uff0c\u524d\u592b\u5434\u5947\u9686\u8fd9\u6837\u8bc4\u4ef7\u5979(4) |work=china.com |date=5 June 2017 |accessdate=14 November 2019 |language=zh}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! English title !! Chinese title !! Role  !! Notes\n|-\n| 1989 || ''Beijing Girl'' || {{lang|zh-Hans|\u5317\u4eac\u5c0f\u599e}} ||  Jin Jing || \n|-\n|}\n\n===Television==